Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.944
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:06.350
BRIAN ROBERTSON:
All right, welcome.

00:00:06.350 --> 00:00:10.370
So first, just a little
bit of background-- I'm

00:00:10.370 --> 00:00:11.170
an entrepreneur.

00:00:11.170 --> 00:00:12.910
My background's in
software development.

00:00:12.910 --> 00:00:15.060
I started coding
very, very young

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:18.320
when I found a Commodore 64
and a bunch of other older

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:20.470
machines, which by the
way, I've seen many of them

00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:21.250
in your lobby.

00:00:21.250 --> 00:00:26.250
And I just [INAUDIBLE] today
and go hang out in there now.

00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:29.820
So from my early background
in software developments,

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:31.410
I did that for a while.

00:00:31.410 --> 00:00:33.760
Went through the whole
management ranks--

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:35.590
climbed the management ladder.

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:37.920
And for me, it
was a sense of I'm

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:40.570
noticing the human issues
getting in the way of what

00:00:40.570 --> 00:00:43.136
I was doing in the
technology world

00:00:43.136 --> 00:00:44.760
almost as much as
any of the technology

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:47.290
issues we're facing--
the process, the people,

00:00:47.290 --> 00:00:49.100
the way we work
together, and all that.

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:51.160
So I got really
fascinated by that.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:54.860
And I worked in an aerospace
company at the time.

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:58.150
And it won an award for being
the best mid-size company

00:00:58.150 --> 00:00:59.510
to work for in America, right?

00:00:59.510 --> 00:01:01.510
A really sizable award.

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:05.255
And I realized I wasn't
really satisfied there.

00:01:05.255 --> 00:01:06.630
Despite that,
don't get me wrong.

00:01:06.630 --> 00:01:07.629
The benefits were great.

00:01:07.629 --> 00:01:10.130
The perks were incredible.

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:12.570
I realized what I really
wanted was an environment where

00:01:12.570 --> 00:01:16.599
I could really use my talents
fully where anything I sensed

00:01:16.599 --> 00:01:18.640
that could be better I
could do something with it

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:19.940
and act on it.

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:24.280
And all of the free lunches and
perks and even a really cool,

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:26.850
fun culture wasn't
enough for me.

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:29.360
I just wanted to
use my creativity.

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:31.556
And there was something
getting in the way.

00:01:31.556 --> 00:01:33.930
And after a while, I realized
what was getting in the way

00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:36.250
was something around the
way we work together--

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:39.180
the structure, the
politics, the bureaucracy.

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:39.870
I had ideas.

00:01:39.870 --> 00:01:42.240
And I couldn't get them
socialized enough in the system

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:43.510
to change anything.

00:01:43.510 --> 00:01:46.120
And I'd go to meetings and we
wouldn't even get to my topics

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:48.480
because they were
painful and long and all

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:50.490
of these other things
that get in the way of us

00:01:50.490 --> 00:01:51.230
using our gifts.

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:54.240
So I eventually dropped
out of that whole system

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.120
and started my own company.

00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:58.484
And my goal with
that company was

00:01:58.484 --> 00:01:59.650
I want to find a better way.

00:01:59.650 --> 00:02:02.320
There's got to be a
better way to organize.

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:04.490
And so my company
became a laboratory.

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:06.560
And we experimented
over many years

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:09.460
as we grew that business
just looking for how can we

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:11.660
work together more effectively.

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:13.810
And I had a bunch of
ideas, most of which

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:15.380
proved to be terrible ideas.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:17.630
And I won't share them with you.

00:02:17.630 --> 00:02:19.330
But over the years
of experimenting,

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:21.000
some stuff actually worked.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.240
So eventually we would
name it Holacracy.

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:27.240
But where this came from was
not from a bunch of ideas,

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.190
not from a bunch of
theory, definitely

00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:30.820
not from a management
consultant.

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:33.050
It was from a bunch
of entrepreneurs

00:02:33.050 --> 00:02:35.550
trying to build a
business and figuring out

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:37.240
what works through
trial and error

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.510
and a lot of experimentation.

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:42.450
So with that said,
let me introduce you

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:45.700
to the category of how to
think about this thing.

00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:49.790
I think about Holacracy as
a new social technology.

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:52.110
And being a software
guy by background,

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:54.560
I think a lot about
technology and usually

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:56.430
when people talk
about technology,

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:59.690
they're talking about the
physical technologies hardware.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:03.590
Gadgets, devices or even
software internet-- whatever.

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:05.560
But there's this other
class of technology--

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:09.050
social technologies-- that
actually in a lot of ways

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:11.810
have been fundamental
in our whole progress

00:03:11.810 --> 00:03:14.380
as a human species,
at least as much

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:16.920
as our actual physical
technologies--

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:20.870
technologies like rule
of law and democracy

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:22.420
and all of the
other ways that we

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:26.960
humans group together, organize,
and find ways to interconnect.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:29.940
Right, those are
social technologies.

00:03:29.940 --> 00:03:33.040
And yet, when we look at the
social technology in place

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:36.410
in most companies, it
looks like something

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:38.630
out of the feudal empire.

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:41.690
There are kings and
lords and barons

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:44.520
and down at the
bottom, peasants.

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:48.480
There's this management
hierarchy that really matured.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.010
This technology matured
about 100 years ago.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:54.310
This technology came about
when the telegraph was still

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:57.900
an exciting, new
communication mechanism.

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:00.640
And management
technology has not really

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:04.400
evolved in any major
leaps since then.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:07.500
It's an old operating system.

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:09.870
And it's not that there's
anything wrong with it per se.

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:13.080
I think it's just quickly
becoming obsolete.

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:16.660
The world today is moving faster
than our management systems are

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:19.209
able to adapt and respond.

00:04:19.209 --> 00:04:22.949
If we want nimble, agile,
responsive organizations,

00:04:22.949 --> 00:04:24.490
how can we make them
more responsive?

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:27.510
Perhaps-- perhaps we can look
at this fundamental social

00:04:27.510 --> 00:04:30.510
technology and
innovate in that area.

00:04:30.510 --> 00:04:33.370
How else could we run a company?

00:04:33.370 --> 00:04:36.550
And I think this is a
worthwhile exploration

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:39.030
because I think a lot
of the challenges we

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:42.930
see in organizations today--
the bureaucracy, the politics--

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:45.570
they are hard to
solve by just patching

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:49.110
some new process on top of
the way we run a company.

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:52.530
In many ways, I think our
companies today are perfectly

00:04:52.530 --> 00:04:55.900
designed to achieve significant
issues with bureaucracy,

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:58.520
politics, communication issues,
and all of the other stuff

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.991
that we suffer from
in most organizations.

00:05:00.991 --> 00:05:01.490
Right?

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:05.700
It's a feature, not a bug--
perhaps not an intended one.

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:09.860
But there's something about this
fundamental social technology

00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:12.940
that leaves a lot to be desired.

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:14.950
And it also brings us
some important features.

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:15.990
This gets us alignment.

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:17.740
It gets us accountability.

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:20.680
It gets us some way of breaking
down the work and scaling.

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:22.500
And we need these things too.

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:24.792
So when we talk about
new social technologies

00:05:24.792 --> 00:05:27.250
for running an organization,
I think it's really important.

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:29.770
We don't just throw
out all structure.

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:32.530
And that's not what a
Holacracy is all about.

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.410
It's about replacing
this structure

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:36.730
with some other
way of structuring

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:40.700
an organization that's maybe
a little more responsive.

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:42.450
And why it might we
want to change this?

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:44.590
And what issues might
we need to deal with?

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:46.870
Well, when we talk about
structure at this level,

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:49.500
we're really
talking about power.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:52.742
Who has the authority to do
what in the organization?

00:05:52.742 --> 00:05:54.200
What can we expect
from each other?

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:55.727
These are deep issues.

00:05:55.727 --> 00:05:57.560
And when humans are
involved, sometimes what

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:00.269
we get with our nice
org charts on paper

00:06:00.269 --> 00:06:01.810
is a management
hierarchy that really

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:02.910
looks something like this.

00:06:05.450 --> 00:06:07.020
Give you a second
to take that in.

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.020
Have you seen any of
these actually at play

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:11.610
in a real organization
by the way?

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:13.350
I've seen at least
a couple of these

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:18.610
actually at play as the real
power structure in a company.

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:20.720
And it's no wonder
humans are involved.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:22.680
We're messy creatures, right?

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:26.530
We bring our egos and our
drama and our politics in.

00:06:26.530 --> 00:06:28.970
And when we don't have a
good way of structuring

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:31.910
the work around what we're
trying to do together,

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:36.240
we often end up resorting to
the social dynamics at play.

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:38.950
So what else can we do?

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:40.950
Well, there's another
way-- another way

00:06:40.950 --> 00:06:43.270
of achieving order,
which is what

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:44.540
we want in any organization.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:46.550
We need some kind of order.

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:49.920
And if I look at the city
around us, we're in New York

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:50.530
right now.

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:53.530
As much as it looks like pure
chaos out there on one hand,

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:57.060
there's actually quite a
bit of social order at play.

00:06:57.060 --> 00:06:59.340
I can pretty much fly
into New York and trust

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:01.620
that I'm going to be able
to get a taxi, find a hotel,

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:05.040
get some food, and whatever
else I might need to do.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:07.530
And the right place--
the right services

00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:10.820
will be there to support me and
without a boss directing them

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:11.689
all around.

00:07:11.689 --> 00:07:13.730
There's no boss that made
sure the taxi was there

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:15.860
to pick me up-- the hotel,
the whatever, right?

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:17.410
It just worked.

00:07:17.410 --> 00:07:20.220
So we ended up with
emergent order--

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:23.630
the kind of order that
is not imposed top down

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:27.560
from a centralized plan, but
the kind of order that shows up

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.240
when you have the right
framework of rules

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:32.440
and individuals with
the freedom to act

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:34.470
within that framework of rules.

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:37.970
We see this every day
in our modern society.

00:07:37.970 --> 00:07:39.640
Yet when we go
into a company, we

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:41.442
see something very different.

00:07:41.442 --> 00:07:43.400
We see a very different
way of achieving order.

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:46.450
It's an attempt to
centrally plan and control

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:49.779
and achieve an order by imposing
one as opposed to putting

00:07:49.779 --> 00:07:51.320
in place the right
framework of rules

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:53.970
and allowing order to show up.

00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:56.270
And many companies are
somewhere between those extremes

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:56.970
of course.

00:07:56.970 --> 00:07:58.570
They're experimenting
and exploring

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:01.570
and many individuals when they
see structure that doesn't make

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:03.670
sense, say, well,
forget that, I'm

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:06.360
going to do what makes sense.

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:08.676
And the structure
often gets in the way.

00:08:08.676 --> 00:08:10.800
And I think that's why when
we talk about structure

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:13.220
in companies, there's
a lot of people

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:16.730
that have an allergic reaction
to the idea of structure.

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:19.570
They associate it
with bureaucracy.

00:08:19.570 --> 00:08:21.070
But I'd say that's
because we've got

00:08:21.070 --> 00:08:24.820
the wrong structure or the
structure that is in the way.

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:26.740
When I walk around
New York, I don't

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:29.780
experience the structure of
the rules of the game at play

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:31.070
as limiting me.

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:32.199
It's actually enabling me.

00:08:32.199 --> 00:08:33.740
I kind of like those
two yellow lines

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:35.948
in the center of the road
as much as sometimes people

00:08:35.948 --> 00:08:36.590
ignore them.

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:37.309
That's structure.

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:37.929
It's limiting.

00:08:37.929 --> 00:08:42.460
And yet it's enabling speed
and freedom and agility.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:43.880
The right structure does that.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:46.860
So how can we bring
into our organizations

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:48.110
a different type of structure.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.600
And what would that look like?

00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:53.100
Well, the first thing
that Holacracy does

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:55.330
is introduce a
framework of rules

00:08:55.330 --> 00:08:56.770
just like we have in societies.

00:08:56.770 --> 00:08:59.750
And it's captured
in a constitution.

00:08:59.750 --> 00:09:03.470
So once a company tastes
Holacracy, they experience it,

00:09:03.470 --> 00:09:06.044
they get a sense of it, and they
decide they want to do this.

00:09:06.044 --> 00:09:07.460
They want to move
forward with it.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:10.980
The first move is for the
CEO or department head

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:15.250
or whoever's adopting this
to sign a declaration ceding

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:19.680
their power into
this constitution,

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:22.570
saying I am no
longer above the law,

00:09:22.570 --> 00:09:25.630
but I'm subject to the same
rules that everyone else is.

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:27.440
And here's a framework
that we'll all

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:30.120
be bound by as we go about
doing our work together

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.350
in this organization.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:33.960
It's a pretty big shift.

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:38.040
Can you imagine a CEO you know
or a significant department

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:41.320
manager or something like that
signing a declaration saying

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:44.540
I'm ceding my authority to
just do whatever I want and run

00:09:44.540 --> 00:09:48.300
things as the boss into a
framework of rules like this?

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:49.850
It's a cool shift.

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:52.560
And this constitution
you can actually

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:53.977
find it on GitHub
for those of you

00:09:53.977 --> 00:09:55.143
from a technical background.

00:09:55.143 --> 00:09:56.450
It's an open source document.

00:09:56.450 --> 00:09:58.700
It's a fundamental
rules of the game.

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:01.330
I like to think of
Holacracy like a new sport.

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:03.650
And these are the
rules of this sport.

00:10:03.650 --> 00:10:05.570
And it's a framework
that tells us

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:08.450
all how we can act and
interact and expect

00:10:08.450 --> 00:10:11.967
things of each other and
change things in the company.

00:10:11.967 --> 00:10:14.550
So let's look at some of the key
shifts that this set of rules

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.280
introduces.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:19.960
And the first one is any of you
have a static job description?

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:22.980
Like something that hasn't been
updated in at least months,

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:25.752
if not years that
maybe is out of date--

00:10:25.752 --> 00:10:27.460
that probably was out
of date by the time

00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:29.300
it rolled off the printer?

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:32.580
When was the last time you
ran to your jobs description

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:35.930
to figure out what you
should be focused on today?

00:10:35.930 --> 00:10:36.430
Right?

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:38.320
Anyone?

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:39.810
No, didn't think so.

00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:40.310
Right?

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:43.990
So that's because they're
pretty much useless.

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:46.130
I should say they're
useful for some things.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:48.720
We write them so that we
can post a job, great.

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.390
But really, how
much clarity does

00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:53.340
a typical job description
offer for our day-to-day work?

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:54.230
Really, nothing.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:56.920
They are bureaucratic artifacts.

00:10:56.920 --> 00:11:00.090
Holacracy replaces those with
a new type of structure--

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:03.650
a new way of describing the
work-- the roles at play.

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:05.880
And they're dynamically updated.

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:09.090
So with Holacracy instead of
having one job description,

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:11.130
you might fill 20
different roles.

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.810
And you might fill 20 roles
in lots of different teams

00:11:13.810 --> 00:11:15.090
all across the company.

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:18.400
It doesn't just have to be one
place in this siloed structure.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:20.250
So you might fill lots
of different roles.

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:22.070
And each one is a
little chunk of work.

00:11:22.070 --> 00:11:25.010
It's one discrete function.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:28.330
And the way of describing these
roles is much more grounded.

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:29.330
So it has real clarity.

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:31.730
And companies running
with holocracy-- people

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:34.220
do go and reference their
job descriptions-- their role

00:11:34.220 --> 00:11:37.930
descriptions regularly because
they have really good clarity

00:11:37.930 --> 00:11:41.340
that's the result of the
team's collective learning.

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:44.180
And the reason is because
they're updated regularly

00:11:44.180 --> 00:11:46.740
by the people doing the work.

00:11:46.740 --> 00:11:48.810
So there's a process--
it's called governance.

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:50.690
I'll talk about it in
a few minutes where

00:11:50.690 --> 00:11:52.970
each team gets together
and they learn together

00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:55.610
and they capture that learning
and distill down what do we

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:57.560
need to be doing differently?

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:59.597
Who needs to be focused on what?

00:11:59.597 --> 00:12:01.430
And we capture that
learning in these roles.

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:03.054
So they're living,
breathing, entities.

00:12:03.054 --> 00:12:05.684
And they have
meaningful clarity.

00:12:05.684 --> 00:12:06.600
That's one difference.

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:07.920
Here's another.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:10.850
In most companies, you've
got a manager who delegates

00:12:10.850 --> 00:12:12.350
some authority to you.

00:12:12.350 --> 00:12:14.630
Rarely is that really clear.

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:17.920
Rarely do you know exactly
what your authority is.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:20.550
More often than not, it's kind
of like you have the authority

00:12:20.550 --> 00:12:22.924
to do whatever you're doing
as long as the manager thinks

00:12:22.924 --> 00:12:24.542
it's generally the
right thing to do.

00:12:24.542 --> 00:12:26.250
And as soon as they
don't, they'll get in

00:12:26.250 --> 00:12:27.333
and they'll tell you that.

00:12:27.333 --> 00:12:30.510
And then you better
align with what they say.

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:33.230
With Holacracy, instead of this
kind of delegated authority

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:37.080
that can be pulled back or
micromanaged at any point,

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:39.850
it's truly a distributed
authority paradigm.

00:12:39.850 --> 00:12:42.470
So according to the constitution
and the fundamental rules

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:46.800
of this game, when you have a
role that we created together

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:48.580
through this
governance process, you

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.110
have the autonomy
and the authority

00:12:51.110 --> 00:12:54.940
to do anything that makes sense
to you to get the job done--

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:57.160
to get the job of that
role done unless there's

00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:59.670
an explicit rule against it.

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:02.150
So instead of needing
permission to act and to make

00:13:02.150 --> 00:13:04.410
sure your manager is
happy all the time,

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:06.080
you've got autonomy
and authority

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:10.000
to go lead your role however
it makes sense to you.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.770
And when we discover that
there's a constraint we need,

00:13:12.770 --> 00:13:16.780
we will create that minimally
sufficient just in time.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:18.892
So instead of needing
permission to act first,

00:13:18.892 --> 00:13:21.350
you have a blanket grant to do
whatever makes sense to you.

00:13:21.350 --> 00:13:23.683
And as we learn together,
we'll start adding constraints

00:13:23.683 --> 00:13:25.220
just when we need them.

00:13:25.220 --> 00:13:29.100
And there's no manager to
undelegate that authority.

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:31.980
So in a company like mine,
we run with Holocracy.

00:13:31.980 --> 00:13:34.810
Everyone has a real
autonomy and authority.

00:13:34.810 --> 00:13:36.410
Everyone can make
different decisions

00:13:36.410 --> 00:13:39.380
and everyone knows what that
is and what the boundaries are.

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:42.230
So it's a lot like living
in a society, right?

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:45.640
I know I can do whatever I
want in my house, my property.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:47.620
But if I want to go
take my neighbor's car,

00:13:47.620 --> 00:13:49.340
I should probably
get his permission.

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:51.580
That's his territory--
his property.

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:52.830
Holacracy does the same.

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:56.039
It makes clear what's
mine to lead and control.

00:13:56.039 --> 00:13:57.580
And I don't need
anyone's permission.

00:13:57.580 --> 00:13:58.200
It's mine.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:13:59.040
It's my territory.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:00.310
I can do whatever I want.

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:02.000
And it makes clear
where my neighbors

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.330
are-- where the boundaries
are and what we can

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:05.635
expect from each other as well.

00:14:05.635 --> 00:14:07.760
Because when we have a
autonomy in an organization,

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:10.790
it's got to come with
a responsibility.

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:12.110
So here's another shift.

00:14:12.110 --> 00:14:15.180
What this does when we have
constantly updating roles

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:17.230
with real authority
is instead of

00:14:17.230 --> 00:14:19.240
these large-scale
re-organizations--

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:21.940
every few years and somebody
comes in and changes

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:23.260
the whole structure.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:26.360
Instead, we're doing
micro-reorganizations

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:29.140
constantly in every team.

00:14:29.140 --> 00:14:33.040
So we are rapidly iterating on
our organizational structure.

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:35.146
And this isn't done at
the top and handed down.

00:14:35.146 --> 00:14:36.270
This is done in every team.

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:39.060
Every team has a governance
process that they go through.

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:41.020
It might be twice a month.

00:14:41.020 --> 00:14:43.370
In a more mature
organization with Holacracy,

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:45.810
it might be once a month
or every other month.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:47.890
We pull back and we say
what are we learning

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:51.360
and how do we restructure our
team to capture that learning.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:53.850
So rapid iterations,
micro-restructurings

00:14:53.850 --> 00:14:56.680
throughout the organization.

00:14:56.680 --> 00:15:00.690
And what that means because
we have this transparent rules

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:02.870
system and we're constantly
changing and adjusting

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:04.980
and learning together
is when we need

00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:08.590
to align-- get alignment, which
we need, in most companies,

00:15:08.590 --> 00:15:11.990
the only way you can
really get change enacted

00:15:11.990 --> 00:15:15.180
is by working the
political system at play.

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:16.305
You build consensus.

00:15:16.305 --> 00:15:17.680
Anyone find yourself
in a meeting

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:21.270
at any point where you're
really there to build buy-in.

00:15:21.270 --> 00:15:22.920
Or you were there
because someone else

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:25.120
is trying to build your
buy-in for some change.

00:15:25.120 --> 00:15:28.800
And we play this game in
the system to get alignment.

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:31.180
And that's actually
really expensive.

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:33.600
If every time I want to
make a change to something

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:36.270
and it's significant, I have to
build buy-in and get consensus

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:37.057
from everyone.

00:15:37.057 --> 00:15:38.140
There's a lot of meetings.

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:40.370
They're painful.

00:15:40.370 --> 00:15:42.550
And there's an
alternative, which

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:45.755
is get clear whose
is this to lead.

00:15:45.755 --> 00:15:47.130
And then that
person doesn't need

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:49.810
to go get alignment and build
buy-in and get consensus.

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:52.050
They know this is mine to lead.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:53.950
And I can go get input
from whoever I want.

00:15:53.950 --> 00:15:55.460
And at the end of the day,
I'm going to make the call.

00:15:55.460 --> 00:15:57.720
And I'm going to lead
this and make a decision.

00:15:57.720 --> 00:16:00.420
And everyone can have
that in their area.

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.430
And if we want to
influence the person,

00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:05.050
we have a rule system to do it.

00:16:05.050 --> 00:16:07.100
This is the point of the
Holacracy constitution.

00:16:07.100 --> 00:16:08.960
It gives us a
framework where if I

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:11.220
need to expect something
different from you than what

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:14.480
you're doing, I have a structure
in which I can propose that.

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:16.340
And we can clarify
the expectations

00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:18.810
between us-- the boundaries
or the constraints

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:20.260
we're operating in.

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:23.180
So instead of doing that just
through political pressure,

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:25.104
we can simply go use the rules.

00:16:25.104 --> 00:16:27.020
So what we end up with
is something a lot more

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:30.950
like a sport where once
everyone knows the rules,

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:33.360
you usually don't see the
players thinking about them.

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:34.680
They're just on the field.

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:36.290
They're playing the game.

00:16:36.290 --> 00:16:37.870
They all have autonomy.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:38.732
You don't see.

00:16:38.732 --> 00:16:40.940
You don't see athletes
calling meetings to figure out

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:42.450
who should pass the ball next.

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:44.780
Are you OK with me
passing the ball to you?

00:16:44.780 --> 00:16:47.590
Is that OK now?

00:16:47.590 --> 00:16:51.295
You also don't see managers
directing the field.

00:16:51.295 --> 00:16:52.670
When people are
out on the field,

00:16:52.670 --> 00:16:55.030
they're using their
judgment in their roles

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:57.090
with autonomy leading.

00:16:57.090 --> 00:16:58.850
And everyone's
doing that together.

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:01.250
And the rules are simply
the framework behind them.

00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:02.459
They're not in the way.

00:17:02.459 --> 00:17:04.750
They're simply what gives
you a game in the first place

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:06.595
to play.

00:17:06.595 --> 00:17:08.720
Now learning the game is
a totally different story.

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.136
And you've got to
learn the rules.

00:17:10.136 --> 00:17:12.060
And there's a whole
learning curve to this.

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:13.690
But once you know
the rules, they

00:17:13.690 --> 00:17:17.480
fade away to the background
if it's the right game.

00:17:17.480 --> 00:17:19.900
So let's look a little more
about how this actually

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:23.089
shows up-- what it actually
looks like-- how it works.

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:25.190
And here's an example of a role.

00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:28.210
So this is a role I fill--
Holacracy spokesperson.

00:17:28.210 --> 00:17:30.390
And it has a purpose.

00:17:30.390 --> 00:17:32.620
Crystallize and convey
the Holacracy brand--

00:17:32.620 --> 00:17:34.520
reveal its why to the world.

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:36.490
So I also have some
accountabilities.

00:17:36.490 --> 00:17:38.830
These are things that
others can expect of me.

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:41.600
So to go along with my
autonomy in this role,

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:44.140
I have some responsibilities
and captures them and tells

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:46.300
everyone else what
they can expect.

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:49.690
And when I fill a role
like this in Holacracy,

00:17:49.690 --> 00:17:51.364
I don't need permission
from a manager.

00:17:51.364 --> 00:17:52.280
There are no managers.

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:54.820
I don't need permission
from anyone to do my job.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:56.690
I can do anything that
makes sense to me.

00:17:56.690 --> 00:18:00.500
I can make any decision
and take any action

00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:02.290
to express that purpose.

00:18:02.290 --> 00:18:06.250
As long as I don't violate an
explicit rule or constraint

00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:08.280
that's been documented
somewhere-- so

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.000
broad grant of authority.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:15.250
And here's how we might see some
of those constraints play out.

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:16.120
Here's another role.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:19.000
This is our web architect
role filled by a colleague

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.210
of mine, Olivier.

00:18:20.210 --> 00:18:23.080
And it has its own purpose--
clear and sexy website

00:18:23.080 --> 00:18:26.060
for Holacracy and
HolacracyOne, my company.

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:29.960
And notice this website-- or
sorry, this role Web Architect,

00:18:29.960 --> 00:18:31.400
has a domain.

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:34.210
Domain-- think of that
as property of this role.

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:34.900
Its domain.

00:18:34.900 --> 00:18:37.620
It controls our website.

00:18:37.620 --> 00:18:40.990
What that tells me is although I
have all the freedom in my role

00:18:40.990 --> 00:18:42.862
to do whatever
makes sense to me,

00:18:42.862 --> 00:18:44.320
if I want to mess
with our website,

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:47.340
I need this role's permission.

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:49.590
Kind of like in our society,
I know I have the freedom

00:18:49.590 --> 00:18:51.355
to lead my life however I want.

00:18:51.355 --> 00:18:52.980
But if I want to use
my neighbor's car,

00:18:52.980 --> 00:18:54.710
I better get his permission.

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:57.610
We have a framework of clear
boundaries with clear property.

00:18:57.610 --> 00:18:59.612
And we know who controls what.

00:18:59.612 --> 00:19:01.570
And we know what we can
expect from each other.

00:19:01.570 --> 00:19:02.420
We have agreements.

00:19:02.420 --> 00:19:04.830
We might have a neighborhood
association or what

00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:06.690
have you-- the same thing here.

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:09.520
So I know that I have a
lot of freedom in my role.

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.620
But he controls the
website-- integrate with him

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:15.180
if I want to do something
on the web and vice versa.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:16.120
He's got a purpose.

00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:18.370
He's got the authority to
do anything that makes sense

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:19.610
to him to get the job done.

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:21.910
And he needs to honor
other people's property.

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:23.570
So what we end up
with is a system

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:26.430
where there is no boss
delegating and directing

00:19:26.430 --> 00:19:27.350
everyone else.

00:19:27.350 --> 00:19:29.300
Yet there are clear ownership.

00:19:29.300 --> 00:19:32.340
So it's not a consensus
based system at all.

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:34.590
Every role knows
here's my territory.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:37.100
And I can lead
that autocratically

00:19:37.100 --> 00:19:39.550
within my responsibilities
and any constraints

00:19:39.550 --> 00:19:42.560
that we have defined
in governance together.

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:45.040
And that governance
process happens

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:46.560
in what we call a circle.

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:50.200
So circles group roles together.

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:51.890
The metaphor I like
for this-- think

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:53.880
of the roles like little cells.

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:55.350
Each one has an autonomy.

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:59.020
Every cell in your body has its
own self-organizing process--

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:01.740
its own structure-- its own
area that it deals with.

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:03.160
Its own processes.

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:05.930
And yet each cell is
also part of an organ.

00:20:05.930 --> 00:20:09.070
And that organ doesn't
violate the autonomy of cells.

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:11.450
Rather it adds
another larger entity

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:13.490
that integrates
them-- that deals

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:15.430
with the flows between cells.

00:20:15.430 --> 00:20:19.830
And that's what a circle does
in Holacracy for its roles.

00:20:19.830 --> 00:20:22.580
So this is nature's way
of scaling and organizing.

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:25.580
And a circle in Holacracy
is like that organ.

00:20:25.580 --> 00:20:28.994
And what circles do every
month or thereabouts--

00:20:28.994 --> 00:20:30.410
they'll hold a
governance meeting.

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:32.410
And this happens
asynchronously between meetings

00:20:32.410 --> 00:20:36.470
as well where every role
in the circle-- anyone who

00:20:36.470 --> 00:20:39.360
fills a role is invited to
participate in the governance

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:41.520
process of the circle.

00:20:41.520 --> 00:20:43.410
So everyone who fills
a role-- this circle--

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:45.785
it's our marketing circle
outreach we call it--

00:20:45.785 --> 00:20:48.910
it includes the two roles we
looked at-- my spokesperson

00:20:48.910 --> 00:20:50.820
role-- the web architect.

00:20:50.820 --> 00:20:52.570
And we show up in this
governance meeting.

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:56.070
And that's where we define the
boundaries between our roles.

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:58.920
That's where we define what's
his to control-- what's mine.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:00.540
What do we expect
from each other.

00:21:00.540 --> 00:21:02.957
We can create new roles
whenever we need them.

00:21:02.957 --> 00:21:04.540
And, remember, people
fill many roles.

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:06.240
So that doesn't
mean hiring someone.

00:21:06.240 --> 00:21:08.570
I fill 20-some
roles in my company.

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:10.470
So we can create
any role we want

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:13.840
and then go shop around and
find the best fit for that role.

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:14.930
We can change roles.

00:21:14.930 --> 00:21:16.420
We can add
expectations on roles,

00:21:16.420 --> 00:21:17.836
constrain roles--
whatever we need

00:21:17.836 --> 00:21:20.920
to do through this
governance process.

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:24.100
And in that governance
process, anyone filling a role

00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:25.300
has a voice.

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:27.580
But we only use this
collective process

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:31.020
to define the boundaries-- to
define the scope of authority

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:32.590
of the different roles.

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:34.880
Day to day when we're
executing, we're

00:21:34.880 --> 00:21:38.029
not trying to come to
consensus on every decision.

00:21:38.029 --> 00:21:39.570
We're just getting
the job done given

00:21:39.570 --> 00:21:41.910
the authority we've been
granted through this governance

00:21:41.910 --> 00:21:43.930
process.

00:21:43.930 --> 00:21:45.860
Even in the governance
process, it's

00:21:45.860 --> 00:21:47.789
not a consensus-based process.

00:21:47.789 --> 00:21:49.330
And it's one that's
actually grounded

00:21:49.330 --> 00:21:50.800
in logic and arguments.

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:52.810
Anyone can show
up and say, here's

00:21:52.810 --> 00:21:56.050
something that got in the
way of getting the work done.

00:21:56.050 --> 00:21:57.450
Here's an example.

00:21:57.450 --> 00:22:00.780
And to resolve that and
prevent it from ever recurring,

00:22:00.780 --> 00:22:03.820
I'd like to add a new
expectation onto our web

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:06.000
architect role or whatever.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.516
And then there's a process of
sorting that proposal through.

00:22:08.516 --> 00:22:09.890
Everyone gets some
input into it.

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:11.870
Although you can't just
say I don't like it.

00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:14.120
You got to say, well, here's
why that would cause harm

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:14.621
in my work.

00:22:14.621 --> 00:22:16.661
And then we'll integrate
and we'll sort that out.

00:22:16.661 --> 00:22:18.560
And we'll come out with
some new governance

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:23.310
that defines new expectations
for the team that work.

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:26.430
And then we can go embody those
expectations, executing them,

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:28.429
get the job done day to day.

00:22:28.429 --> 00:22:29.970
So we have a
self-organizing process.

00:22:29.970 --> 00:22:30.760
And this scales.

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:32.300
This is a fractal structure.

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:35.880
So every level kind of
works the same, right?

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:38.070
So we don't just have
roles within circles.

00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:41.380
We have circles within
circles within circles.

00:22:41.380 --> 00:22:44.050
And this is, again, a
very organic process.

00:22:44.050 --> 00:22:45.850
So just like the
human body-- cells

00:22:45.850 --> 00:22:47.850
within organs
within organ systems

00:22:47.850 --> 00:22:51.460
within an overall organism.

00:22:51.460 --> 00:22:53.980
There's no boss cell in
your body believe it or not.

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:54.480
Right?

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:56.979
There's no one boss cell that
is telling all the other cells

00:22:56.979 --> 00:22:58.600
what to do and how to work.

00:22:58.600 --> 00:23:00.720
Rather every cell
has autonomy and yet

00:23:00.720 --> 00:23:04.180
they also have to be aligned
with the broader organ.

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:06.777
They have to figure out how
they work with the other cells.

00:23:06.777 --> 00:23:08.360
And that's kind of
what the organs do.

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:11.394
They group them together
and deal with flows.

00:23:11.394 --> 00:23:13.560
And then there are larger
systems that group organs.

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:14.393
That's what this is.

00:23:14.393 --> 00:23:16.056
So it's a fractal structure.

00:23:16.056 --> 00:23:17.430
Again, a lot like
nature, this is

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:21.620
nature's way of dealing
with complexity at scale.

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:25.200
And within this, everything's
changing constantly.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:27.240
Every one of these
roles-- they're dynamic.

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:29.670
They're updated in regular
governance meetings happening

00:23:29.670 --> 00:23:31.310
in every circle as
we learn together

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:33.380
to keep it grounded and real.

00:23:33.380 --> 00:23:35.290
So it's a very dynamic process.

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:38.181
And this is why when
if you read the press,

00:23:38.181 --> 00:23:40.430
there's some misunderstandings
out there in Holacracy.

00:23:40.430 --> 00:23:43.290
One of them is that this
is a "flat" structure

00:23:43.290 --> 00:23:44.780
or no structure.

00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:45.510
And it's not.

00:23:45.510 --> 00:23:47.990
It's actually more structured
than a typical management

00:23:47.990 --> 00:23:49.380
hierarchy.

00:23:49.380 --> 00:23:51.630
It's just a different
kind of structure.

00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:53.680
And it's one that is
really trying to align

00:23:53.680 --> 00:23:55.022
with what's actually needed.

00:23:55.022 --> 00:23:57.480
It's the kind of structure more
like those two yellow lines

00:23:57.480 --> 00:23:58.082
in the road.

00:23:58.082 --> 00:23:59.790
Not the kind that gets
in your way that's

00:23:59.790 --> 00:24:01.930
bureaucracy and limits
you, but the kind that

00:24:01.930 --> 00:24:04.700
enables us to go fast together.

00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:08.657
It's minimal, just-in-time
dynamic structure.

00:24:08.657 --> 00:24:09.490
But it is structure.

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:10.540
And its clarity.

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:11.680
Who can decide what?

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:13.310
Who can expect what from whom?

00:24:13.310 --> 00:24:16.200
All of that.

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:19.200
And let's talk about one
other piece, which is what

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:21.830
drives change in the system?

00:24:21.830 --> 00:24:23.530
And, again, the same
thing that drives

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:27.120
change in many living
systems-- tension.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:31.340
And with Holacracy, we don't
mean tension in a negative way.

00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:33.410
So I define tension
as simply the feeling

00:24:33.410 --> 00:24:37.240
you get when you sense a
gap between where we are

00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:40.540
and where we could
be or some potential

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:43.000
that's better in some way.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:44.880
We sense a lot of these.

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:48.840
Yet, how many people can say,
you know, anything I sense.

00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:52.320
Any tension I sense, any gap,
anything that could be better,

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:53.920
I know exactly
what to do with it

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:56.310
to drive a rapid,
meaningful change anywhere

00:24:56.310 --> 00:24:58.490
in the organization.

00:24:58.490 --> 00:25:02.430
Very few companies today can
fully harness the sensing

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:04.020
that everyone within is doing.

00:25:04.020 --> 00:25:05.880
More often than
not, you get people

00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:08.790
who have sensed issues
for years and don't

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:10.280
know how to drive change.

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:12.270
So all they can do
is complain about it

00:25:12.270 --> 00:25:14.460
or get apathetic
or wait and bide

00:25:14.460 --> 00:25:17.710
their time for an opportunity.

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:21.850
None of that is
using that wisdom.

00:25:21.850 --> 00:25:23.350
None of that is
actually taking what

00:25:23.350 --> 00:25:25.680
we're sensing and
incorporating that

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:28.910
into a learning
organism of the company.

00:25:28.910 --> 00:25:31.030
So the goal of Holacracy
is pretty simple.

00:25:31.030 --> 00:25:33.590
It's to make sure any
tension sensed by anyone

00:25:33.590 --> 00:25:35.740
anywhere in the
organization has a place

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:37.980
to go to get rapidly
and reliably processed

00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:41.170
into meaningful change,
at least to the extent

00:25:41.170 --> 00:25:42.930
that it's relevant to
the company's work--

00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:45.830
its purpose in the world.

00:25:45.830 --> 00:25:50.890
And this also keeps us
really, really grounded.

00:25:50.890 --> 00:25:52.710
How many organizational
designs do you

00:25:52.710 --> 00:25:56.575
see today that are the
product of somebody's vision?

00:25:56.575 --> 00:25:57.950
And, actually,
that sounds great.

00:25:57.950 --> 00:26:00.300
But I think there's a
lot of issues with that.

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:03.310
Anyone here in the
software development world?

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:05.217
I'm imagining many
of you, right?

00:26:05.217 --> 00:26:06.675
Have you ever seen
software designs

00:26:06.675 --> 00:26:08.909
that are the result of
somebody's good ideas

00:26:08.909 --> 00:26:10.950
and vision and they apply
this whole architecture

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:13.520
to a software product
as opposed to listening

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:15.360
to what the customers
want and listening

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:18.250
to what the code even is
telling you and keeping

00:26:18.250 --> 00:26:23.050
a more agile, adaptive design,
letting the design tell you

00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:25.390
what it wants to be
instead of you imposing all

00:26:25.390 --> 00:26:26.720
of your good ideas up front?

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:28.960
We learned a long time
ago in the software world

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:31.190
that that kind of
waterfall design process

00:26:31.190 --> 00:26:32.800
doesn't lead to
great results when

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:35.090
you have dynamic complexity
in the world-- when

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:37.050
you have a lot of
change, a lot of input,

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:38.850
and you've got to learn.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:42.340
Our organizations today
are in that world too.

00:26:42.340 --> 00:26:45.250
And get the approach we take
to designing organizations

00:26:45.250 --> 00:26:48.070
is very much
somebody's big vision,

00:26:48.070 --> 00:26:51.230
grand ideas, top-down
imposed applied design.

00:26:51.230 --> 00:26:52.540
And then it's static.

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:54.370
And it doesn't change that much.

00:26:54.370 --> 00:26:58.100
And the best we can do in
that is try to work around it.

00:26:58.100 --> 00:27:00.350
And we experience the structure
is getting in the way,

00:27:00.350 --> 00:27:01.770
limiting bureaucratic structure.

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:07.290
If we want to respond
to a world that

00:27:07.290 --> 00:27:09.360
is changing fast with
our companies today,

00:27:09.360 --> 00:27:12.770
we need companies that can
be responsive to everything

00:27:12.770 --> 00:27:17.590
sensed by everyone within and
let the design evolve itself.

00:27:17.590 --> 00:27:20.920
So Holocracy can be described
as an evolutionary design

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:23.040
algorithm rhythm for a company.

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:24.530
What it does is
let the tensions we

00:27:24.530 --> 00:27:27.540
sense tell us where we need
to change our organization's

00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:29.360
design.

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:32.010
So the design evolves one
tension at a time by somebody

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:34.474
sensing what's getting
in the way of the work

00:27:34.474 --> 00:27:36.640
and then doing something
about it, responding to it,

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:39.960
adapting-- changing the design
of the company and testing it.

00:27:39.960 --> 00:27:41.160
How does that work?

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:42.080
Is that better?

00:27:42.080 --> 00:27:44.020
Or do we sense more tensions?

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:44.520
Great!

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:45.180
More tensions.

00:27:45.180 --> 00:27:45.679
Good.

00:27:45.679 --> 00:27:48.456
Let's adapt it again.

00:27:48.456 --> 00:27:50.330
So a company running
with Holacracy, the goal

00:27:50.330 --> 00:27:52.110
is not to be without tension.

00:27:52.110 --> 00:27:54.630
It's just that the same ones
aren't plaguing us for years

00:27:54.630 --> 00:27:55.900
that we're not listening to.

00:27:55.900 --> 00:27:57.610
We want to deal with
those so that we

00:27:57.610 --> 00:28:00.660
are free to sense the
next tension as we adapt

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:04.250
and evolve in our environment.

00:28:04.250 --> 00:28:07.369
That is the whirlwind
tour of Holacracy.

