So you gave us a straight
overview of the system.

00:32:41.139 --> 00:32:42.430
I'm curious about the outcomes.

00:32:42.430 --> 00:32:44.180
So who's using this?

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:48.020
And are they're really
seeing significant results

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.840
that are different than, say,
a traditional organization?

00:32:50.840 --> 00:32:53.470
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, so right
now today as best we can tell,

00:32:53.470 --> 00:32:56.280
there's somewhere around a
few hundred companies out

00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:57.570
there doing this.

00:32:57.570 --> 00:33:00.969
And we don't have any
actual hard data metrics

00:33:00.969 --> 00:33:02.010
that we've collected yet.

00:33:02.010 --> 00:33:03.732
I really look forward to that.

00:33:03.732 --> 00:33:06.190
Harvard Business School is
doing an actual research project

00:33:06.190 --> 00:33:07.830
right now on one of
the companies going

00:33:07.830 --> 00:33:08.670
through the transition.

00:33:08.670 --> 00:33:10.250
And I hope that'll
be the first step

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:12.040
to getting some real
academic research

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:14.230
and what effect it has.

00:33:14.230 --> 00:33:16.390
And so I don't have any
actual hard numbers.

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:18.680
I have a lot of
anecdotal stories.

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:21.010
And one of the
challenges of this

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:24.630
is it's such a
fundamental change.

00:33:24.630 --> 00:33:27.480
How do you know whether--
even great numbers.

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:29.620
One company reported
massive increases.

00:33:29.620 --> 00:33:31.020
They showed the revenue graph.

00:33:31.020 --> 00:33:32.070
And it was like this.

00:33:32.070 --> 00:33:34.570
And then it just went like this
once they adopted Holacracy.

00:33:34.570 --> 00:33:35.370
But I'm skeptical.

00:33:35.370 --> 00:33:36.100
I love the data.

00:33:36.100 --> 00:33:38.950
And if somebody wants numbers,
I'll throw that one at them.

00:33:38.950 --> 00:33:41.570
But how do you know
that was because

00:33:41.570 --> 00:33:45.170
of Holacracy versus anything
else in their world?

00:33:45.170 --> 00:33:45.920
I look at this.

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:48.070
It's like changing
your operating system.

00:33:48.070 --> 00:33:49.670
So I'm a Mac user.

00:33:49.670 --> 00:33:53.000
I upgraded from being a
PC user several years ago,

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:57.270
jumped into the Mac, and for
me, it's just a better platform.

00:33:57.270 --> 00:33:59.612
And my productivity, I
feel like it's higher.

00:33:59.612 --> 00:34:01.320
I think I can get
stuff done more easily.

00:34:01.320 --> 00:34:04.250
The operating system is
in the way less often.

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:07.950
It gives me great platform
to build on top of.

00:34:07.950 --> 00:34:10.870
But I could tie any specific
metrics I might want to.

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:12.080
And it's hard to tie it back.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:14.389
It's more just I have
a better platform.

00:34:14.389 --> 00:34:16.181
So for me, the best
judge-- and what

00:34:16.181 --> 00:34:17.889
I encourage all of
our clients and anyone

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:21.719
trying this to really tune
into is your own experience

00:34:21.719 --> 00:34:24.949
of is it easier or
harder to use your voice

00:34:24.949 --> 00:34:27.480
and drive some positive change?

00:34:27.480 --> 00:34:30.300
And I think that's a really
interesting, reliable metric.

00:34:30.300 --> 00:34:34.330
And if you look at, for me, when
I switched from Windows to Mac,

00:34:34.330 --> 00:34:37.239
I just feel like I can get
stuff done faster and easier.

00:34:37.239 --> 00:34:39.679
And I hear the same from
companies that switch to this

00:34:39.679 --> 00:34:40.699
all the time.

00:34:40.699 --> 00:34:43.770
And that's actually why
many executives and CEOs

00:34:43.770 --> 00:34:45.590
make the switch
after they try it

00:34:45.590 --> 00:34:47.250
even just for a couple of days.

00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:50.692
Through the different processes,
Holacracy shows up and adds.

00:34:50.692 --> 00:34:52.900
And at the end of that, they
have a direct experience

00:34:52.900 --> 00:34:55.750
of how did this way of
dealing with my tensions

00:34:55.750 --> 00:34:58.437
compare to what I would
have done in the old system.

00:34:58.437 --> 00:35:00.020
And they get to see
in the old system,

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:01.895
I would've talked to a
bunch of people, built

00:35:01.895 --> 00:35:05.150
a bunch of buy-in, called some
meetings, wrestled with it,

00:35:05.150 --> 00:35:08.480
and maybe a year
later, we would change.

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:10.120
In the new system,
it happens faster.

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:13.850
So just one example-- in Zappos,
which runs with Holacracy

00:35:13.850 --> 00:35:17.660
as well, there was a meeting
of one of their circles

00:35:17.660 --> 00:35:19.830
where they restructured
a business unit.

00:35:19.830 --> 00:35:22.850
And this was apparently
a contentious issue.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:26.010
There was a lot of intense
feelings in the room.

00:35:26.010 --> 00:35:28.049
And there was a
proposal to restructure,

00:35:28.049 --> 00:35:29.590
slice and dice this
thing, and change

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:31.006
some of what was
expected from it.

00:35:31.006 --> 00:35:34.090
And at the end of
about 20, 25 minutes,

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:37.150
we ended up with a
new, integrated output

00:35:37.150 --> 00:35:39.960
of total restructure
to this unit.

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:41.940
And with everyone there,
bought into the path

00:35:41.940 --> 00:35:45.110
forward, even after people
raised significant issues

00:35:45.110 --> 00:35:47.620
with it, we sorted all them out.

00:35:47.620 --> 00:35:49.540
20, 25 minutes later we're done.

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:51.210
They came up to me
afterwards and said

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:56.110
we've been wrestling with that
issue for literally years--

00:35:56.110 --> 00:35:59.270
through hours and hours and
hours and hours of talking,

00:35:59.270 --> 00:36:02.040
political influencing, meetings.

00:36:02.040 --> 00:36:03.910
And we never got to
clear resolution.

00:36:03.910 --> 00:36:05.619
And it just carried
it through inertia.

00:36:05.619 --> 00:36:06.910
We just kept it the way it was.

00:36:06.910 --> 00:36:07.786
Nobody liked it.

00:36:07.786 --> 00:36:09.660
But we couldn't agree
on what to do about it.

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:11.450
And now in 20 minutes,
we just nailed it.

00:36:11.450 --> 00:36:13.000
And everyone's comfortable.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:14.849
Not that we've got
the perfect result,

00:36:14.849 --> 00:36:16.140
but that we've got a next step.

00:36:16.140 --> 00:36:18.180
And we can come back to
this meeting next month

00:36:18.180 --> 00:36:20.630
and continue to evolve it
further as we learn what works

00:36:20.630 --> 00:36:22.410
and what doesn't about this.

00:36:22.410 --> 00:36:25.040
So to me, that's the
metric that I like to.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:27.350
Is it easier or
harder to drive change

00:36:27.350 --> 00:36:31.439
and to get tensions
addressed in the system,

00:36:31.439 --> 00:36:33.730
AUDIENCE: Hey, Brian, thanks
for coming and explaining.

00:36:33.730 --> 00:36:36.760
It really is interesting.

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:40.440
So I understand the
structure and the freedom

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:43.090
and the principles of Holacracy.

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:44.730
In my experience,
one of the detriments

00:36:44.730 --> 00:36:49.090
I see to organizations is
more about ego and insecurity.

00:36:49.090 --> 00:36:51.620
And so I'm just
wondering how those--

00:36:51.620 --> 00:36:53.370
especially when you
give a lot of freedom,

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:55.357
you're going to-- this
idea of land grabbing

00:36:55.357 --> 00:36:56.440
is always the term, right?

00:36:56.440 --> 00:36:58.280
And you get these people
that are operating

00:36:58.280 --> 00:37:01.070
in that respect and the damage
it can do to an organizations.

00:37:01.070 --> 00:37:03.030
How does that work
in your system?

00:37:03.030 --> 00:37:06.630
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, so I wish
I had an extra hour for you.

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:09.010
This is one of my favorite
parts of Holacracy, actually.

00:37:09.010 --> 00:37:10.980
And it shows up in
some of the rules

00:37:10.980 --> 00:37:14.060
of the decision making process
used in the governance meeting.

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:17.350
And those rules are there
to keep egos in check

00:37:17.350 --> 00:37:19.810
from influencing
your organization.

00:37:19.810 --> 00:37:22.870
It doesn't make people
saints that have no egos.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:26.700
What it does is prevent the egos
from dominating the meeting.

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:28.450
And there's all sorts
of interesting rules

00:37:28.450 --> 00:37:30.040
and a facilitation
process that's

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:31.612
used to cut through that.

00:37:31.612 --> 00:37:33.070
If you want to see
more of that, we

00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:34.990
have a video simulation
of the governance

00:37:34.990 --> 00:37:36.448
meeting on our
website that you can

00:37:36.448 --> 00:37:37.970
go watch and see those rules.

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:40.820
And they're specifically
about how they deal with ego.

00:37:40.820 --> 00:37:43.670
But just to give you one a
little example, a little taste.

00:37:43.670 --> 00:37:45.740
In the governance
meeting process,

00:37:45.740 --> 00:37:48.450
let's say someone shows up
and they propose a change.

00:37:48.450 --> 00:37:51.470
I think we should add this
expectation to this role

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:53.830
or give this rule this
authority, whatever.

00:37:53.830 --> 00:37:56.780
There's a place where everybody
gets to then raise objections

00:37:56.780 --> 00:37:57.840
to that.

00:37:57.840 --> 00:37:59.470
But objections are
not just I don't

00:37:59.470 --> 00:38:02.260
like it or all
the egoic response

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:03.410
that sometimes people have.

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:06.150
It doesn't solve my thing.

00:38:06.150 --> 00:38:09.320
Instead, there's these rules
of what is a valid objection

00:38:09.320 --> 00:38:10.209
and what's not.

00:38:10.209 --> 00:38:12.500
And if somebody just shows
up-- here is a real example.

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:13.750
I had a team.

00:38:13.750 --> 00:38:16.352
It was a project
management team.

00:38:16.352 --> 00:38:18.060
They were managing a
big, new initiative.

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:20.240
And somebody brought a proposal.

00:38:20.240 --> 00:38:23.930
Someone else gets really
fired up, starts to jump in,

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:24.640
and interrupt.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:27.280
And there's rules, actually,
even about giving people

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:28.830
space to speak and
not interrupting

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:30.810
so I stop the person
I was facilitating--

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:32.992
stop the person until
it got to her turn.

00:38:32.992 --> 00:38:34.700
And then she had a
bunch to say about it.

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:36.510
We got to the objection part.

00:38:36.510 --> 00:38:37.870
And she says, objection!

00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:41.030
Yeah, this has been an
issue for us for years.

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:42.980
And I'm so frustrated by it.

00:38:42.980 --> 00:38:44.100
And that won't solve it.

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.027
And she went on and on and on.

00:38:46.027 --> 00:38:48.610
The poor proposer was not trying
to solve that person's issue.

00:38:48.610 --> 00:38:50.370
They were trying to solve
their own little piece of it

00:38:50.370 --> 00:38:52.210
that they needed to
get their work done.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:56.150
And here's somebody else
from an intentionally--

00:38:56.150 --> 00:38:57.230
she was trying to help.

00:38:57.230 --> 00:39:00.180
But it was getting in the way of
this person solving one issue.

00:39:00.180 --> 00:39:01.160
So she says objection.

00:39:01.160 --> 00:39:01.910
She says all this.

00:39:01.910 --> 00:39:04.650
And then using one of the
rules in the constitution,

00:39:04.650 --> 00:39:07.360
I asked her this issue
you're having now--

00:39:07.360 --> 00:39:10.122
is that going to be
created by her proposal?

00:39:10.122 --> 00:39:12.080
Or is that already an
issue that you would like

00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:14.425
to solve independent of this.

00:39:14.425 --> 00:39:16.800
And, of course, she says, oh
no, that's already an issue.

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:19.420
I've been suffering
from it for years.

00:39:19.420 --> 00:39:21.850
And I said, OK, well then
that's not a valid objection,

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:23.490
according to the
rules of the game

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:25.390
because our goal is not
addressed her issue.

00:39:25.390 --> 00:39:27.010
It's only to address
the proposers.

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:28.400
That's it-- that one issue.

00:39:28.400 --> 00:39:29.780
So for her to
raise an objection,

00:39:29.780 --> 00:39:33.450
she has to be able to say here's
why that proposal will get

00:39:33.450 --> 00:39:35.100
in the way of me doing my work.

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:36.960
And she has to
describe it concretely.

00:39:36.960 --> 00:39:38.260
Not just, I don't like it.

00:39:38.260 --> 00:39:41.270
It doesn't solve my pet
issue that I want to solve

00:39:41.270 --> 00:39:42.610
or anything else.

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:45.270
So there's a lot of rules like
that that are just subtle.

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:46.440
They are questions.

00:39:46.440 --> 00:39:48.300
And they help sort
through and keep

00:39:48.300 --> 00:39:51.790
us laser-focused on processing
one tension at a time

00:39:51.790 --> 00:39:55.080
sensed by one person without
anyone else's stuff getting

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:56.197
in the way.

00:39:56.197 --> 00:39:57.780
And after that, I
invited her-- you're

00:39:57.780 --> 00:39:59.434
welcome to add your
item to the agenda.

00:39:59.434 --> 00:40:00.850
And when we get
there, we'll focus

00:40:00.850 --> 00:40:03.720
on processing your
attention however we can.

00:40:03.720 --> 00:40:05.730
So it's really about
giving everyone

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:07.820
a space to process their
tensions without all

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:09.145
the egos getting in the way.

00:40:09.145 --> 00:40:10.107
AUDIENCE: Cool, thanks

00:40:10.107 --> 00:40:12.190
BRIAN ROBERTSON: And there's
more the book as well

00:40:12.190 --> 00:40:13.645
about that whole process.

00:40:13.645 --> 00:40:15.070
Yeah?

00:40:15.070 --> 00:40:18.250
AUDIENCE: Hi, I totally get how
these processes can help make

00:40:18.250 --> 00:40:19.790
