00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:49.980
lines-- big picture.

00:40:49.980 --> 00:40:52.560
What are we trying to achieve
with our overall business

00:40:52.560 --> 00:40:53.890
model and all that.

00:40:53.890 --> 00:40:57.294
We have another role that looks
at how can we support companies

00:40:57.294 --> 00:40:59.460
that are trying to do it
themselves-- do it yourself

00:40:59.460 --> 00:41:01.710
Holacracy adoption,
which is really hard.

00:41:01.710 --> 00:41:04.027
But we have a role that
that's the big picture of you.

00:41:04.027 --> 00:41:05.110
They're looking years out.

00:41:05.110 --> 00:41:06.230
What tools can we create?

00:41:06.230 --> 00:41:07.515
How can we make that easier?

00:41:07.515 --> 00:41:10.140
So whatever you need to do, just
show up, process that tension,

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:11.920
and create whatever you need to.

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:15.130
Another example-- the governance
meetings although they often

00:41:15.130 --> 00:41:18.149
are dealing with micro stuff
because often the micro stuff

00:41:18.149 --> 00:41:19.690
is what's actually
getting in the way

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:21.610
most practically in the work.

00:41:21.610 --> 00:41:24.160
Sometimes though they really
do pull up really high levels.

00:41:24.160 --> 00:41:27.140
So we had one just last
week actually where

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:28.880
one of our team
members showed up

00:41:28.880 --> 00:41:33.040
and he had a circle team
that was doing some work.

00:41:33.040 --> 00:41:34.890
And it just didn't feel right.

00:41:34.890 --> 00:41:36.820
So he showed up and he
said, I propose we just

00:41:36.820 --> 00:41:40.550
remove that circle, drop
it, toss it out, kill it.

00:41:40.550 --> 00:41:42.240
It was an interesting proposal.

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:44.302
And there were a lot of
objections-- reasons why

00:41:44.302 --> 00:41:46.760
that circle is actually doing
important work that we really

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:47.579
need.

00:41:47.579 --> 00:41:49.120
And then to resolve
those objections,

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:51.280
we pulled up to the
kind of 50,000 foot view

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:54.400
and looked at what is the circle
doing that really matters?

00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:55.940
And why does the
circle feel weird?

00:41:55.940 --> 00:41:57.910
And what can we do
with those functions?

00:41:57.910 --> 00:42:00.430
And, ultimately, we
restructured our whole vision.

00:42:00.430 --> 00:42:02.450
Inside of about 45
minutes, we completely

00:42:02.450 --> 00:42:06.160
restructured, killed one
circle, put functions elsewhere.

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:10.500
And it's really cool to see that
kind of dynamic reorganization

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:13.890
happening regularly in
companies instead of it's static

00:42:13.890 --> 00:42:15.820
and its stuck in
what they're doing.

00:42:15.820 --> 00:42:21.770
And it is often the big,
strategic solution almost,

00:42:21.770 --> 00:42:23.600
but one tension at a time.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:25.650
And for me, this is the
really interesting thing

00:42:25.650 --> 00:42:29.630
is it's like imagine a company
is a ball of yarn of tensions.

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:31.780
Every thread is a tension.

00:42:31.780 --> 00:42:33.780
And it's all woven together.

00:42:33.780 --> 00:42:35.690
The temptation in
a lot of companies

00:42:35.690 --> 00:42:37.706
is to look at the ball
of yarn, pull back

00:42:37.706 --> 00:42:39.330
to get really strategic,
and figure out

00:42:39.330 --> 00:42:41.830
how are we going to untangle
all of these different tensions

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:43.140
and solve it all.

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:45.240
Holacracy invites a
slightly different approach,

00:42:45.240 --> 00:42:48.960
which is grab one thread--
pull that one thread out.

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:51.760
Disentangle just that one
thread-- that one tension

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:54.136
from everything else instead
of trying to solve all of it

00:42:54.136 --> 00:42:56.676
at once, which often means we
talk about it forever and don't

00:42:56.676 --> 00:42:57.840
actually change anything.

00:42:57.840 --> 00:42:59.160
Solve that one thread.

00:42:59.160 --> 00:42:59.660
Good.

00:42:59.660 --> 00:43:01.840
Now solve the next one
until, eventually, there's

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:02.715
no more ball of yarn.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:09.490
AUDIENCE: So going
by your terminology,

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:11.440
I think a lot of
tensions in organizations

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:16.370
are around three pillars, which
are motivations, incentives,

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:17.410
and vision.

00:43:17.410 --> 00:43:17.910
Right?

00:43:17.910 --> 00:43:21.440
So a founder, like, for
example, Larry here,

00:43:21.440 --> 00:43:23.690
might have a vision that,
hey, I want to is the world.

00:43:23.690 --> 00:43:26.300
I want to Google to be
present 30 years from now.

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:28.920
But I'm pretty sure there's some
employee-- someone at Google

00:43:28.920 --> 00:43:30.130
who is thinking, you know what?

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:30.880
Screw all of that.

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:33.540
I want to make my paycheck
bigger in the next six months.

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:34.780
And that's all I care about.

00:43:34.780 --> 00:43:36.560
If Google starts
going down, who cares?

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:38.790
I'll just jump ship
to some other company.

00:43:38.790 --> 00:43:41.130
So how-- and this
is just one example.

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:43.880
But how do you align
those kind of tensions?

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:46.325
And I think that's why the
management structure exists

00:43:46.325 --> 00:43:48.650
that someone says, no,
you want to do that?

00:43:48.650 --> 00:43:49.787
Go do it somewhere else.

00:43:49.787 --> 00:43:51.370
This is how Google
wants to do things.

00:43:51.370 --> 00:43:54.320
And that's where the
top-down hierarchy comes in.

00:43:54.320 --> 00:43:57.160
BRIAN ROBERTSON:
Yeah, so a huge piece

00:43:57.160 --> 00:43:59.660
of the puzzle-- not the only
piece, but a huge piece here,

00:43:59.660 --> 00:44:00.690
is purpose.

00:44:00.690 --> 00:44:03.260
So Holacracy is a
purpose-driven system,

00:44:03.260 --> 00:44:05.830
which means the whole thing
we're organizing around

00:44:05.830 --> 00:44:07.790
is what is the ultimate
purpose of the company.

00:44:07.790 --> 00:44:09.790
And how are we going to
express it in the world.

00:44:09.790 --> 00:44:10.665
And that breaks down.

00:44:10.665 --> 00:44:13.070
So every role has its
piece of that-- its purpose

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:14.790
within this overall system.

00:44:14.790 --> 00:44:18.260
So that's one of the alignment
functions in Holacracy

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:21.340
is it's all about aligning
around purpose as opposed

00:44:21.340 --> 00:44:24.190
to aligning around a person
like a manager, which

00:44:24.190 --> 00:44:25.940
a lot of management
hierarchies fall into.

00:44:25.940 --> 00:44:28.200
People really align around
what the manager wants

00:44:28.200 --> 00:44:30.020
or how they see the
world as opposed

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:31.660
to around the purpose at play.

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:34.610
And that also gives an
element of motivation too.

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:38.650
For me, when you get to
fully use your autonomy,

00:44:38.650 --> 00:44:40.400
your capacity,
your creative gifts

00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:43.390
to serve a purpose that
you've chosen to serve.

00:44:43.390 --> 00:44:46.240
There's a certain kind
of intrinsic motivation

00:44:46.240 --> 00:44:47.164
that can show up.

00:44:47.164 --> 00:44:48.330
Not that it's guaranteed to.

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:50.440
Some people are still
doing it for the paycheck.

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:52.910
And then there's a whole
range in between of, hey,

00:44:52.910 --> 00:44:53.850
I want the paycheck.

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:55.950
But this is cool work.

00:44:55.950 --> 00:44:59.500
But I see at least a shift
towards that when companies

00:44:59.500 --> 00:45:02.670
shift to have really clear
purpose that is compelling,

00:45:02.670 --> 00:45:05.410
that's broken down, and everyone
has a place and the autonomy

00:45:05.410 --> 00:45:08.990
to choose something that they
want to express and do it,

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:11.910
you get a different kind of
motivational force, which often

00:45:11.910 --> 00:45:16.300
then has pay and other concerns
like that less of a front

00:45:16.300 --> 00:45:17.260
and center focus.

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:18.634
Not that they're
unimportant, but

00:45:18.634 --> 00:45:21.280
at least not the main driver
of motivation anymore.

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:23.640
And Holacracy isn't
a cure-all for that.

00:45:23.640 --> 00:45:26.320
Companies still have to wrestle
with that, even with Holacracy.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:27.838
AUDIENCE: Cool, thanks.

00:45:27.838 --> 00:45:29.272
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah?

00:45:29.272 --> 00:45:30.950
AUDIENCE: Hi, I have
a few questions.

00:45:30.950 --> 00:45:33.230
One is-- you were
talking about pay.

00:45:33.230 --> 00:45:35.290
How do you decide
what people get paid?

00:45:35.290 --> 00:45:36.150
BRIAN ROBERTSON: I
was wondering when

00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:38.640
somebody would ask that because
it comes up in every talk

00:45:38.640 --> 00:45:39.430
I give.

00:45:39.430 --> 00:45:43.150
So to use a metaphor,
again, think of Holacracy

00:45:43.150 --> 00:45:44.960
like a new operating system.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:47.290
It isn't a full,
complete package

00:45:47.290 --> 00:45:49.600
with all the apps you
need in your organization.

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:50.100
Right?

00:45:50.100 --> 00:45:53.065
It's like I love my Mac, but
I download a calendar app

00:45:53.065 --> 00:45:55.190
because I don't particularly
like the built-in one,

00:45:55.190 --> 00:45:55.690
whatever.

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:57.210
I download other apps.

00:45:57.210 --> 00:46:00.360
Holacracy does not tell
you how to do compensation.

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:02.252
But you need an app to do that.

00:46:02.252 --> 00:46:03.460
So there are many approaches.

00:46:03.460 --> 00:46:05.390
And every company
that uses Holacracy

00:46:05.390 --> 00:46:06.765
could do that a
little different.

00:46:06.765 --> 00:46:09.227
They might install a different
app for compensation.

00:46:09.227 --> 00:46:11.560
And the same with a number
of other business processes--

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:14.660
firing, benefits,
all of these things

00:46:14.660 --> 00:46:16.780
are kind of like the
apps of business.

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:18.492
And that's said,
to avoid completely

00:46:18.492 --> 00:46:21.890
dodging the question, let
me give you a common answer.

00:46:21.890 --> 00:46:25.022
Here's one app that's
actually fairly common now.

00:46:25.022 --> 00:46:25.980
It's growing out there.

00:46:25.980 --> 00:46:26.930
My company uses it.

00:46:26.930 --> 00:46:29.540
Zappos is moving to
something like it too.

00:46:29.540 --> 00:46:32.120
And it's a badge-based
compensation app

00:46:32.120 --> 00:46:35.550
where badges represent
skills you've demonstrated

00:46:35.550 --> 00:46:37.639
to your peers that you have.

00:46:37.639 --> 00:46:39.430
So you can earn badges
in different skills.

00:46:39.430 --> 00:46:40.930
There's a library of badges.

00:46:40.930 --> 00:46:42.770
There's a process by
which you can propose

00:46:42.770 --> 00:46:44.830
a new badge-- a new
skill that you think

00:46:44.830 --> 00:46:45.940
needs to be recognized.

00:46:45.940 --> 00:46:48.120
And anyone can initiate that.

00:46:48.120 --> 00:46:50.970
And then anyone who's earned
the same set about badges

00:46:50.970 --> 00:46:52.272
will get paid the same.

00:46:52.272 --> 00:46:54.230
And that's transparent
and everyone can see it.

00:46:54.230 --> 00:46:56.957
If you have this set of badges,
your pay is going to be that.

00:46:56.957 --> 00:46:58.790
And if you get this set
plus these two more,

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:00.390
then your pay is
going to be this.

00:47:00.390 --> 00:47:02.950
And if you think there's a set
of badges that doesn't show up

00:47:02.950 --> 00:47:04.783
there and should have
a different pay level,

00:47:04.783 --> 00:47:06.416
you can propose it
and say, you know,

00:47:06.416 --> 00:47:09.040
these badges are worth this much
and these are worth that much,

00:47:09.040 --> 00:47:11.604
then I think my set of badges
here should be worth this much.

00:47:11.604 --> 00:47:13.520
And there's a process
to evaluate that and get

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:14.650
it put in place.

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:16.550
So what you end
up with is instead

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:19.670
of one linear climb
across a ladder

00:47:19.670 --> 00:47:22.220
and pay is by management,
grade or whatever,

00:47:22.220 --> 00:47:24.430
you end up with a
very dynamic system

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:27.530
where you can grow and
develop in any number of ways

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:29.440
by developing
different skills that

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:30.940
are useful to the organization.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:33.640
And based on the skills you've
demonstrated to your peers

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:36.220
that you are using
clearly and have,

00:47:36.220 --> 00:47:39.500
that will drive your pay in a
very peer-to-peer distributed

00:47:39.500 --> 00:47:40.510
process.

00:47:40.510 --> 00:47:43.140
So that's one approach--
not required by Holacracy,

00:47:43.140 --> 00:47:46.560
but a common app that's
Holacracy compatible.

00:47:46.560 --> 00:47:47.490
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:47:47.490 --> 00:47:50.570
And I want to ask
one more thing.

00:47:50.570 --> 00:47:53.920
You have all these roles the
people decide on and define.

00:47:53.920 --> 00:47:56.370
And then you have all the
people in your organization.

00:47:56.370 --> 00:47:58.967
What happens if someone's
role disappears and they

00:47:58.967 --> 00:48:00.050
need to go somewhere else?

00:48:00.050 --> 00:48:01.200
Or you need to fill new
roles in your circle.

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:03.100
And you need to get
people from somewhere.

00:48:03.100 --> 00:48:04.020
How does that happen?

00:48:04.020 --> 00:48:05.770
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, think
of it like a marketplace.

00:48:05.770 --> 00:48:07.140
You got your buyers and sellers.

00:48:07.140 --> 00:48:10.490
And you need to connect them
and find the right transactions.

00:48:10.490 --> 00:48:13.000
So we talk about the
role marketplace,

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:16.170
which is all these roles,
even in a small company.

00:48:16.170 --> 00:48:18.430
20 people-- you might
have hundreds of roles

00:48:18.430 --> 00:48:19.430
that need to get filled.

00:48:19.430 --> 00:48:21.940
And there are new ones
showing up constantly.

00:48:21.940 --> 00:48:24.150
So there's an
internal marketplace

00:48:24.150 --> 00:48:27.320
that develops of, hey, we've
got a new role in this circle.

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:28.070
Here's what it is.

00:48:28.070 --> 00:48:30.610
And somebody's pitching to try
to find someone to fill it.

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:32.780
And you get some candidates that
are looking for new roles that

00:48:32.780 --> 00:48:33.880
are not completely booked.

00:48:33.880 --> 00:48:36.759
Or they just want something new
and creative add to their mix.

00:48:36.759 --> 00:48:38.050
And so they're shopping around.

00:48:38.050 --> 00:48:39.200
And they find this role.

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:40.720
And then there's, of
course, still a need

00:48:40.720 --> 00:48:42.178
to make sure they're
the right fit.

00:48:42.178 --> 00:48:44.691
So there's another role that
is assigning people to roles

00:48:44.691 --> 00:48:46.940
and making sure they're the
right fit for those roles.

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:48.440
And that's going
to the market maker

00:48:48.440 --> 00:48:50.780
that's bring them together.

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:52.510
And lots of different
companies will then

00:48:52.510 --> 00:48:53.970
do things to make that easier.

00:48:53.970 --> 00:48:58.480
Zappos use-- we have a
software app that supports

00:48:58.480 --> 00:49:00.090
companies using Holacracy.

00:49:00.090 --> 00:49:02.520
They're using the API to
build a whole role marketplace

00:49:02.520 --> 00:49:06.100
app as an extension of that
because they have 1,500 people

00:49:06.100 --> 00:49:07.177
and lots of roles.

00:49:07.177 --> 00:49:08.760
So they're making
it easier for people

00:49:08.760 --> 00:49:12.352
to search and tag roles and
find the right fits for them.

00:49:12.352 --> 00:49:13.310
AUDIENCE: Cool, thanks.

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:15.684
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Cool, thanks.

00:49:15.684 --> 00:49:17.100
AUDIENCE: I have
a quick question.

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:19.090
Thanks for coming.

00:49:19.090 --> 00:49:23.250
Now I was thinking
that Holacracy--

00:49:23.250 --> 00:49:25.370
on paper, that sounds great.

00:49:25.370 --> 00:49:26.380
It's transparent.

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:28.710
It gives people the power.

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:32.200
In case of crisis, it's not
like the South Park episode

00:49:32.200 --> 00:49:34.686
where every bigger
leader keeps walking in

00:49:34.686 --> 00:49:36.060
and keeps changing the process.

00:49:36.060 --> 00:49:38.320
And no one really knows
what the problem is.

00:49:38.320 --> 00:49:42.400
And the problem, actually,
the solver who knows it

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:45.400
is very deep down into the
hierarchy without any power.

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:49.360
That's apparently the problem
that Holacracy seems to solve.

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:51.730
But as an organization
that already

00:49:51.730 --> 00:49:56.810
has its own structure
and its own hierarchy

00:49:56.810 --> 00:49:58.920
built into it-- and the
people have worked hard

00:49:58.920 --> 00:50:04.070
to get high up there--
how do you start injecting

00:50:04.070 --> 00:50:07.850
such things easily and
not like in a big bang

00:50:07.850 --> 00:50:11.150
that people don't forget
the growing pain that much?

00:50:11.150 --> 00:50:13.540
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, to
some extent, I have no idea.

00:50:13.540 --> 00:50:15.820
Good luck.

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:18.530
What I mean by that
is it's huge change.

00:50:18.530 --> 00:50:21.900
And you can't-- at least I have
not yet found a way to avoid

00:50:21.900 --> 00:50:24.029
all of the pain
of transformation.

00:50:24.029 --> 00:50:26.070
You don't change an existing
management hierarchy

00:50:26.070 --> 00:50:28.530
to something like this without
going through some challenge

00:50:28.530 --> 00:50:29.602
along the way.

00:50:29.602 --> 00:50:31.310
That said, we have
found some things that

00:50:31.310 --> 00:50:33.270
might help minimize it some.

00:50:33.270 --> 00:50:36.410
And one for larger organizations
is pilot it somewhere.

00:50:36.410 --> 00:50:38.962
Don't just try to go over
whole organization all at

00:50:38.962 --> 00:50:39.670
once all upfront.

00:50:39.670 --> 00:50:42.210
That's hugely painful.

00:50:42.210 --> 00:50:46.350
Find a department, division,
team, subsidiarr-- something

00:50:46.350 --> 00:50:50.700
that has enough insulation from
the broader corporate system

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:53.315
to say we're going to do things
differently on this team.

00:50:53.315 --> 00:50:54.440
And that's what Zappos did.

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:56.160
They didn't start
across 1,500 people.

00:50:56.160 --> 00:50:58.550
They started in a department
of about 100 people.

00:50:58.550 --> 00:51:00.544
And they piloted
it there and got

00:51:00.544 --> 00:51:02.460
built in internal
expertise, which helped them

00:51:02.460 --> 00:51:03.790
with their broader rollout.

00:51:03.790 --> 00:51:04.620
So they did that.

00:51:04.620 --> 00:51:06.036
That's one technique.

00:51:06.036 --> 00:51:07.910
Another is there's lots
of ways to support it

00:51:07.910 --> 00:51:10.000
with the right support,
coaching, training.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.150
Think of it like
learning a new sport.

00:51:12.150 --> 00:51:15.630
You could try to learn a
new sport or a complex game

00:51:15.630 --> 00:51:17.580
by reading the
rule book and then

00:51:17.580 --> 00:51:19.080
jumping in with
a bunch of people

00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:21.010
that have only read the rule
book and trying to play.

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:22.670
And that's going to
be really awkward.

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:26.160
Or you can get out on the field
people who have played before

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:28.930
and a coach and not worry
about the rules too much.

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:30.680
You'll learn those
as you play, right.

00:51:30.680 --> 00:51:32.970
And then get some
on-the-field instruction.

00:51:32.970 --> 00:51:35.330
And that's going to be a
much easier way to learn.

00:51:35.330 --> 00:51:37.390
So that's another piece of that.

00:51:37.390 --> 00:51:39.250
And finally, there
are certainly a lot

00:51:39.250 --> 00:51:40.420
of things you can
take out of this.

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:42.170
There's a whole chapter
in the book that's

00:51:42.170 --> 00:51:45.415
really just if I can't do
this whole thing, what can I

00:51:45.415 --> 00:51:46.040
pull out of it?

00:51:46.040 --> 00:51:48.560
What little techniques
can I use in my team.

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:50.340
So that can be really valuable.

00:51:50.340 --> 00:51:54.290
Although, that said, if you can,
better to do all of Holacracy

00:51:54.290 --> 00:51:56.230
in part of the company
than part of Holacracy

00:51:56.230 --> 00:51:57.670
in all of the company.

00:51:57.670 --> 00:52:00.260
And what I mean by that is
think of it like playing a game.

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:02.740
You're not really playing
soccer if you adopt one rule.

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:05.350
And if you want to be a
World Cup soccer player,

00:52:05.350 --> 00:52:08.870
you don't get there by mastering
one rule at a time slowly.

00:52:08.870 --> 00:52:11.790
You get there by doing all the
rules when you're six years old

00:52:11.790 --> 00:52:13.710
and being sloppy
and messy at them.

00:52:13.710 --> 00:52:15.455
And you're playing
six-year-old soccer.

00:52:15.455 --> 00:52:17.580
And then eventually your
playing high school soccer

00:52:17.580 --> 00:52:20.820
and professional soccer and
maybe someday World Cup.

00:52:20.820 --> 00:52:23.430
So better to adopt all of
it and part of the company

00:52:23.430 --> 00:52:25.230
and accept it's
going to be messy.

00:52:25.230 --> 00:52:27.350
It's going to be clunky
and awkward and painful

00:52:27.350 --> 00:52:29.140
and slow at first.

00:52:29.140 --> 00:52:31.620
But as you get better and the
rules fade to the background

00:52:31.620 --> 00:52:33.850
and you're now really
playing-- you're

00:52:33.850 --> 00:52:37.712
an athlete-- everything
transforms slowly.

00:52:37.712 --> 00:52:38.420
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:52:38.420 --> 00:52:38.770
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Cool.

00:52:38.770 --> 00:52:39.269
Thank you.

00:52:41.640 --> 00:52:43.030
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

00:52:43.030 --> 00:52:47.220
I just wondered personally
your experience being a CEO

00:52:47.220 --> 00:52:49.850
and then ceding your authority.

00:52:49.850 --> 00:52:53.050
And this thing
that you've created

00:52:53.050 --> 00:52:54.610
has taken on a life of its own.

00:52:54.610 --> 00:52:56.360
I just wondered
what that experience

00:52:56.360 --> 00:52:57.324
has been like for you.

00:52:57.324 --> 00:52:58.240
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah.

00:52:58.240 --> 00:53:01.020
It's been an interesting
one for sure.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:03.740
I have a colleague that
does this work in France.

00:53:03.740 --> 00:53:06.060
And he also is an ex-CEO.

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:07.630
And he said, it's funny.

00:53:07.630 --> 00:53:10.920
A lot of people think that
would be really hard for CEOs

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:13.260
to actually let go
of power like that.

00:53:13.260 --> 00:53:15.070
He said, his
experiences-- most of them

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:16.440
are very happy to do that.

00:53:16.440 --> 00:53:19.170
And it's actually pretty
easy for them, at least

00:53:19.170 --> 00:53:20.070
to make that leap.

00:53:20.070 --> 00:53:23.060
Learning the rules is another
thing and transitioning.

00:53:23.060 --> 00:53:25.220
And I've actually found
something very similar.

00:53:25.220 --> 00:53:29.537
It's not every CEO by any
stretch, but many of them,

00:53:29.537 --> 00:53:31.370
they want a better way
to run their company.

00:53:31.370 --> 00:53:33.980
They know that for this
thing to scale and outgrow

00:53:33.980 --> 00:53:38.220
their limits of themselves,
they need to get power

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:39.220
in other people's hands.

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:41.367
They need to not
hold everything.

00:53:41.367 --> 00:53:43.450
So many of them are already
looking for approaches

00:53:43.450 --> 00:53:45.420
to get them out of being
the central bottleneck

00:53:45.420 --> 00:53:49.470
in the system and yet that still
provide order and transparency

00:53:49.470 --> 00:53:52.680
and don't end up crushing
the company they built.

00:53:52.680 --> 00:53:55.970
So many of them are very
comfortable signing that.

00:53:55.970 --> 00:53:59.510
Where it gets interesting is
when I as a Holacracy coach,

00:53:59.510 --> 00:54:02.480
show up in a meeting with an
executive team or whatever

00:54:02.480 --> 00:54:05.500
and the CEO jumps in just out
of habit and tells somebody,

00:54:05.500 --> 00:54:08.071
hey, why don't you then
take on this or whatever.

00:54:08.071 --> 00:54:09.570
And I have to jump
in and say, whoa,

00:54:09.570 --> 00:54:11.111
you don't actually
have the authority

00:54:11.111 --> 00:54:13.280
to tell that person
what to do anymore.

00:54:13.280 --> 00:54:14.460
You've ceded that authority.

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:16.014
And there's no governance.

00:54:16.014 --> 00:54:17.430
So you have no
right to expect it.

00:54:17.430 --> 00:54:19.263
Would you like to go
to a governance meeting

00:54:19.263 --> 00:54:22.160
and propose an
accountability on his role?

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:23.410
And he might raise objections.

00:54:23.410 --> 00:54:24.910
And then we'll integrate them.

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:27.630
So that's an interesting
than experience.

00:54:27.630 --> 00:54:32.050
But, again, most CEOs I
work with the rise to that

00:54:32.050 --> 00:54:32.850
quite well.

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:34.050
It's still a learning curve.

00:54:34.050 --> 00:54:36.320
And they have to learn
new ways to lead.

00:54:36.320 --> 00:54:39.250
It's probably going back
to what kind of leaders

00:54:39.250 --> 00:54:40.710
adopt something like this.

00:54:40.710 --> 00:54:43.140
It's those that are ready
for going back and learning

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:48.550
new ways to influence and
want something new anyway.

00:54:48.550 --> 00:54:51.200
AUDIENCE: So it seems that the
way that roles are handed out,

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:53.390
there's a big focus on
self-actualization, finding

00:54:53.390 --> 00:54:56.080
something that's a right fit
for you that's exciting for you

00:54:56.080 --> 00:54:58.270
or that you're motivated by.

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:00.722
How do you deal with the
fact that this grunge

00:55:00.722 --> 00:55:02.930
work that has to be done
that's attractive to no one?

00:55:02.930 --> 00:55:05.937
How do you motivate people to
do the crap job, so to speak?

00:55:05.937 --> 00:55:07.520
BRIAN ROBERTSON:
Yeah, so two answers.

00:55:07.520 --> 00:55:09.228
One of them is something
I find happening

00:55:09.228 --> 00:55:13.580
in my company and others often,
which is it's not a problem.

00:55:13.580 --> 00:55:15.060
And I keep expecting it to be.

00:55:15.060 --> 00:55:16.970
I keep waiting for--
we have this new role.

00:55:16.970 --> 00:55:18.154
And it's horrible work.

00:55:18.154 --> 00:55:19.570
I mean, who would
want to do that.

00:55:19.570 --> 00:55:20.770
It sucks.

00:55:20.770 --> 00:55:22.700
And somebody volunteers.

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:25.310
And I haven't quite
figured that one out yet.

00:55:25.310 --> 00:55:27.960
I think it might just
simply be the nature of when

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:30.310
you feel this kind of
peer-to-peer collaboration.

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:32.730
And everyone knows
somebody needs to do that.

00:55:32.730 --> 00:55:34.820
And they've got other
work that they love to do.

00:55:34.820 --> 00:55:37.470
And if I could be of
service and help out and do

00:55:37.470 --> 00:55:40.740
this crap role, then fine,
great, I can do that.

00:55:40.740 --> 00:55:41.860
I'll volunteer.

00:55:41.860 --> 00:55:45.300
So often, it just takes care
of itself, but not always.

00:55:45.300 --> 00:55:47.152
And in that case, the
same thing applies

00:55:47.152 --> 00:55:48.360
in any company still applies.

00:55:48.360 --> 00:55:51.070
Sometimes when you're
hired for a job,

00:55:51.070 --> 00:55:52.497
it comes with conditions.

00:55:52.497 --> 00:55:53.580
And the same is true here.

00:55:53.580 --> 00:55:55.890
You might hire somebody
into this on the condition

00:55:55.890 --> 00:55:59.120
that they accept role
assignments like these.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:01.790
So we'll have that with
somebody we bring in

00:56:01.790 --> 00:56:03.790
and somebody who
joins our company,

00:56:03.790 --> 00:56:05.831
they might have some
agreements that they come in

00:56:05.831 --> 00:56:07.320
with like you'll
fill any roll that

00:56:07.320 --> 00:56:09.430
deals with this kind of work.

00:56:09.430 --> 00:56:12.202
And as part of your employment,
that's an expectation so

00:56:12.202 --> 00:56:14.660
that others know they can assign
that person to those rules

00:56:14.660 --> 00:56:15.560
if the need to.

00:56:15.560 --> 00:56:17.370
AUDIENCE: But it still seems
it's very awkward to enforce,

00:56:17.370 --> 00:56:17.570
right?

00:56:17.570 --> 00:56:19.500
Or even just
underperformance in general

00:56:19.500 --> 00:56:21.340
is something that's
difficult to talk about

00:56:21.340 --> 00:56:22.780
in a group in front of
the large number peers

00:56:22.780 --> 00:56:24.480
that you have to sit
next to every day.

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:28.550
So how do you in
practice point out

00:56:28.550 --> 00:56:31.320
that someone is not fulfilling
the expectations of their role

00:56:31.320 --> 00:56:33.484
in the way that if other
people disagree with you,

00:56:33.484 --> 00:56:35.650
you now feel like you have
to shrivel up in a corner

00:56:35.650 --> 00:56:38.380
and looking at the person.

00:56:38.380 --> 00:56:40.150
BRIAN ROBERTSON:
Yeah, that's awkward.

00:56:40.150 --> 00:56:42.230
So the first line of
defense with Holacracy

00:56:42.230 --> 00:56:44.380
is make it a discussion
that we never

00:56:44.380 --> 00:56:46.550
have to have in the
first place by making

00:56:46.550 --> 00:56:49.810
blindingly obvious the
performance issue to everyone,

00:56:49.810 --> 00:56:51.610
including the person
with the issue.

00:56:51.610 --> 00:56:52.760
That doesn't always work.

00:56:52.760 --> 00:56:54.180
But a lot of
Holacracy's processes

00:56:54.180 --> 00:56:56.540
are designed to get more
transparency of everything--

00:56:56.540 --> 00:56:58.300
what's going on.

00:56:58.300 --> 00:57:01.790
So often I see people
self-selecting out

00:57:01.790 --> 00:57:03.950
before anyone has to talk
about their performance

00:57:03.950 --> 00:57:06.390
because it's really
uncomfortable being the one

00:57:06.390 --> 00:57:09.040
that everyone sees not
performing and you know it.

00:57:09.040 --> 00:57:10.782
And you see it yourself.

00:57:10.782 --> 00:57:12.740
Or sometimes I'll see
people calling themselves

00:57:12.740 --> 00:57:14.740
out and saying,
look, guys, I know

00:57:14.740 --> 00:57:16.429
I'm doing terrible in this role.

00:57:16.429 --> 00:57:18.220
But I don't know that
we have a better fit.

00:57:18.220 --> 00:57:20.386
And I'm holding the line
as best I can until we find

00:57:20.386 --> 00:57:21.670
the right person to do it.

00:57:21.670 --> 00:57:24.160
And then it can be an open,
transparent discussion.

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:25.660
So that's the first
line of defense.

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:26.850
It doesn't always work.

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:28.610
But it happens more
often in companies

00:57:28.610 --> 00:57:30.530
with a lot of transparency.

00:57:30.530 --> 00:57:34.320
And the second is you still
need somebody whose job it

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:35.890
is to watch performance.

00:57:35.890 --> 00:57:37.994
And if they've got a
better fit for a role,

00:57:37.994 --> 00:57:38.910
get someone out of it.

00:57:38.910 --> 00:57:40.160
And put someone else in.

00:57:40.160 --> 00:57:42.335
And that still shows up
in Holacracy as well.

00:57:42.335 --> 00:57:43.960
AUDIENCE: So that
person is essentially

00:57:43.960 --> 00:57:45.180
a manager then in that role.

00:57:45.180 --> 00:57:46.010
BRIAN ROBERTSON: The
interesting thing

00:57:46.010 --> 00:57:48.690
is they have no authority to
tell the person what to do.

00:57:48.690 --> 00:57:50.780
They have no authority
to fire that person.

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:53.669
That person might have 19
other roles in other circles.

00:57:53.669 --> 00:57:55.960
They have no authority to
tell that person what they're

00:57:55.960 --> 00:57:57.960
paid in most
companies using a comp

00:57:57.960 --> 00:58:00.072
app like the one I described.

00:58:00.072 --> 00:58:01.780
They have no authority
to tell the person

00:58:01.780 --> 00:58:04.010
to take on these projects
or these actions.

00:58:04.010 --> 00:58:06.470
All they're doing is
saying, are you the best fit

00:58:06.470 --> 00:58:07.786
I've got for this role?

00:58:07.786 --> 00:58:09.160
Once they put you
in the role, it

00:58:09.160 --> 00:58:11.444
is yours to lead until
they say, OK, great,

00:58:11.444 --> 00:58:12.360
I've got a better fit.

00:58:12.360 --> 00:58:13.810
I'm making a change.

00:58:13.810 --> 00:58:16.671
So it's a function that we
associate with managers.

00:58:16.671 --> 00:58:18.170
And that's one of
the tricky things.

00:58:18.170 --> 00:58:19.800
Those functions do still exist.

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:20.810
They're just different.

00:58:20.810 --> 00:58:23.090
And they're divided out
differently in Holacracy.

00:58:23.090 --> 00:58:23.798
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:58:25.424 --> 00:58:27.590
BRIAN ROBERTSON: All right,
well thank you everyone.

00:58:27.590 --> 00:58:29.200
Appreciate your
time for questions.

00:58:29.200 --> 00:58:29.700
Thank you.

00:58:29.700 --> 00:58:31.660
[APPLAUSE]

00:58:36.904 --> 00:58:38.320
AUDIENCE: Hi, I
got two questions.

00:58:38.320 --> 00:58:42.250
The first one is how do you
deal with existing organizations

00:58:42.250 --> 00:58:44.770
where they are used to
managing with authority.

00:58:44.770 --> 00:58:47.180
They are used to their power
struggles and horse trading

00:58:47.180 --> 00:58:48.020
and all that stuff.

00:58:48.020 --> 00:58:49.770
How do you switch them over?

00:58:49.770 --> 00:58:53.310
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, with
a lot of effort and coaching.

00:58:53.310 --> 00:58:54.640
It's not easy.

00:58:54.640 --> 00:58:56.840
AUDIENCE: What would be,
I guess, the motivation?

00:58:56.840 --> 00:58:58.590
BRIAN ROBERTSON: The
motivation to change?

00:58:58.590 --> 00:59:01.740
Usually, it's somebody at the
top that starts having a vision

00:59:01.740 --> 00:59:05.270
and seeing that this management
hierarchy is limiting

00:59:05.270 --> 00:59:07.740
our flexibility--
our responsiveness.

00:59:07.740 --> 00:59:11.970
Or they like Tony at Zappos
said, I know as we grow,

00:59:11.970 --> 00:59:13.060
bureaucracy sets in.

00:59:13.060 --> 00:59:15.520
And I want to grow more like
a city, more innovation, more

00:59:15.520 --> 00:59:16.490
entrepreneuralism.

00:59:16.490 --> 00:59:19.100
So it's usually somebody
starting to sense the limits.

00:59:19.100 --> 00:59:21.080
If you don't have
anyone experiencing

00:59:21.080 --> 00:59:23.480
any tension about the
current structure,

00:59:23.480 --> 00:59:26.240
it's really difficult to find
anyone that wants to change it.

00:59:26.240 --> 00:59:28.080
But when you find
someone that sees

00:59:28.080 --> 00:59:30.730
the potential for something
different, than Holacracy

00:59:30.730 --> 00:59:33.160
gives a tool for, OK,
here's something different,

00:59:33.160 --> 00:59:34.589
you can just do.

00:59:34.589 --> 00:59:36.130
And then there's
the coaching process

00:59:36.130 --> 00:59:39.090
of shifting managers
from being managers

00:59:39.090 --> 00:59:42.730
to being very different
entrepreneurs, shifting

00:59:42.730 --> 00:59:45.560
other people that are used to
looking to managers to make

00:59:45.560 --> 00:59:47.660
decisions and kind of
hiding in the hierarchy

00:59:47.660 --> 00:59:49.580
to step out and
own their autonomy

00:59:49.580 --> 00:59:50.877
and own their authority.

00:59:50.877 --> 00:59:52.960
There's a lot of coaching
that goes into all that.

00:59:52.960 --> 00:59:53.975
AUDIENCE: And my
second question is

00:59:53.975 --> 00:59:56.320
about how do you deal
with low performers that

00:59:56.320 --> 00:59:59.910
decide to come out with a little
circle that does basically very

00:59:59.910 --> 01:00:00.480
little?

01:00:00.480 --> 01:00:02.540
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah,
the first line of defense

01:00:02.540 --> 01:00:06.890
is simply transparency when it's
obvious to everyone around them

01:00:06.890 --> 01:00:08.930
that that guy's not
performing, that

01:00:08.930 --> 01:00:11.020
creates a lot of peer pressure.

01:00:11.020 --> 01:00:12.690
And that's not the only answer.

01:00:12.690 --> 01:00:14.640
It's just the ideal answer.

01:00:14.640 --> 01:00:16.430
And I see this at
play in companies

01:00:16.430 --> 01:00:19.910
when somebody's poor
performance is blindingly

01:00:19.910 --> 01:00:22.040
obvious to everyone,
the person tends

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:25.750
to opt out of a poor-performing
role pretty quickly.

01:00:25.750 --> 01:00:27.390
When that doesn't
happen, you still

01:00:27.390 --> 01:00:29.510
need somebody else that's making
sure you have the right people

01:00:29.510 --> 01:00:30.390
in the right roles.

01:00:30.390 --> 01:00:32.792
And Holacracy has a
special role in each circle

01:00:32.792 --> 01:00:35.250
whose job it is to get the
right people in the right roles.

01:00:35.250 --> 01:00:36.560
And when somebody's
not performing

01:00:36.560 --> 01:00:38.060
and they need to
make a change, they

01:00:38.060 --> 01:00:40.020
have the authority to do that.

01:00:40.020 --> 01:00:41.950
Now that person can't
tell you what to do.

01:00:41.950 --> 01:00:43.910
They can't tell you
how to do your role,

01:00:43.910 --> 01:00:46.480
but they can find the right
people to give the autonomy to

01:00:46.480 --> 01:00:47.370
in the role.

01:00:47.370 --> 01:00:49.710
So there is still a
function of that as well.

01:00:49.710 --> 01:00:50.960
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Tonya.

01:00:50.960 --> 01:00:52.001
I have so many questions.

01:00:52.001 --> 01:00:54.030
But a follow up
question on that.

01:00:54.030 --> 01:00:58.480
So is there ever an issue with
having more like in group,

01:00:58.480 --> 01:01:00.125
out group issues?

01:01:00.125 --> 01:01:02.250
The way that we deal with
poor performers at Google

01:01:02.250 --> 01:01:02.975
is very private.

01:01:02.975 --> 01:01:04.850
So if you're a poor
performer, your teammates

01:01:04.850 --> 01:01:05.530
don't know about that.

01:01:05.530 --> 01:01:08.010
That's a private conversation
you have with your manager.

01:01:08.010 --> 01:01:10.330
It's not like everyone at a
meetings is like you suck.

01:01:10.330 --> 01:01:11.830
We're all talking about you.

01:01:11.830 --> 01:01:13.910
So I can just see if
there's a system which

01:01:13.910 --> 01:01:19.090
requires like large-- the
larger-- people in masses

01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:21.674
behaving negatively
towards an individual

01:01:21.674 --> 01:01:24.090
because they don't like how
that individual is performing,

01:01:24.090 --> 01:01:27.680
can't that set things up for
the larger issues rather than

01:01:27.680 --> 01:01:29.820
more private
conversations one on one?

01:01:29.820 --> 01:01:30.030
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah.

01:01:30.030 --> 01:01:31.655
I think there would
be a terrible idea.

01:01:31.655 --> 01:01:33.270
But that's not how
Holacracy does it.

01:01:33.270 --> 01:01:35.754
So it provides
more transparency,

01:01:35.754 --> 01:01:36.920
which makes it more obvious.

01:01:36.920 --> 01:01:39.220
But that doesn't mean we
have discussions about it.

01:01:39.220 --> 01:01:41.329
It's just more transparency
of who's doing what.

01:01:41.329 --> 01:01:42.870
What are they getting
that every day?

01:01:42.870 --> 01:01:44.550
That's just more transparent.

01:01:44.550 --> 01:01:47.120
So it's not about
having discussions.

01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:49.160
As a group, this guy sucks.

01:01:49.160 --> 01:01:52.350
It's more about for that person
feeling like, oh, my god.

01:01:52.350 --> 01:01:53.970
My performance is being watched.

01:01:53.970 --> 01:01:54.910
Everyone can see it.

01:01:54.910 --> 01:01:56.640
We don't need to have a
discussion when you know

01:01:56.640 --> 01:01:57.950
that you just have visibility.

01:01:57.950 --> 01:01:59.750
You can't hide
somewhere anymore.

01:01:59.750 --> 01:02:02.310
Everything you do is transparent
for everyone else to see.

01:02:02.310 --> 01:02:03.460
So that's the first sign.

01:02:03.460 --> 01:02:05.660
You still do have one-on-one
private conversations

01:02:05.660 --> 01:02:07.618
when somebody needs to
get removed from a role.

01:02:07.618 --> 01:02:10.250
So there's that special role
I mentioned in each circle.

01:02:10.250 --> 01:02:11.610
That person's not
going to call a meeting

01:02:11.610 --> 01:02:12.650
about that with a group.

01:02:12.650 --> 01:02:14.816
They're going to go talk
to the person and say, hey,

01:02:14.816 --> 01:02:16.400
I think we got you
in the wrong role.

01:02:16.400 --> 01:02:17.997
But firing someone
from a role is not

01:02:17.997 --> 01:02:19.580
the same as firing
them from a company

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:22.550
when they fill 20 other roles,
maybe a different teams.

01:02:22.550 --> 01:02:24.942
So I've been fired
from a role and thanked

01:02:24.942 --> 01:02:26.400
the person firing
me because I knew

01:02:26.400 --> 01:02:27.520
the role was a terrible fit.

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:29.978
And I was just holding the line
until we could get somebody

01:02:29.978 --> 01:02:30.740
better in it.

01:02:30.740 --> 01:02:31.790
And that's great.

01:02:31.790 --> 01:02:33.499
So it's not a
public conversation

01:02:33.499 --> 01:02:34.540
about performance at all.

01:02:34.540 --> 01:02:37.250
It's still a very one-on-one
when that needs to happen.

01:02:37.250 --> 01:02:39.510
AUDIENCE: So it sounds
like while there may not

01:02:39.510 --> 01:02:41.130
be official
managers, there still

01:02:41.130 --> 01:02:43.200
are people that can make
a call on whether or not

01:02:43.200 --> 01:02:45.050
someone should be in a role?

01:02:45.050 --> 01:02:45.340
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Absolutely.

01:02:45.340 --> 01:02:46.339
So think of it this way.

01:02:46.339 --> 01:02:48.990
The functions that you typically
associate with a manager

01:02:48.990 --> 01:02:51.070
get distributed out
into different roles

01:02:51.070 --> 01:02:52.590
and different processes.

01:02:52.590 --> 01:02:55.930
So there is still a role that
can decide who's in which role

01:02:55.930 --> 01:02:57.100
and make changes.

01:02:57.100 --> 01:03:00.030
But that person can't set
your comp-- can't fire you.

01:03:00.030 --> 01:03:02.629
And they can remove you
from that one role, sure.

01:03:02.629 --> 01:03:03.920
They can't tell you what to do.

01:03:03.920 --> 01:03:06.380
They have no authority to
say, hey, I want you to do x.

01:03:06.380 --> 01:03:08.740
Or you're responsible for y.

01:03:08.740 --> 01:03:10.510
That happens through
other processes.

01:03:10.510 --> 01:03:12.360
All they're doing
is looking at here

01:03:12.360 --> 01:03:14.630
is the role we've
defined in governance.

01:03:14.630 --> 01:03:15.827
Who's the right fit for it?

01:03:15.827 --> 01:03:16.910
They get the right fit in.

01:03:16.910 --> 01:03:19.440
And then that person has
autonomy until they jump in

01:03:19.440 --> 01:03:20.750
and need to make a change.

01:03:20.750 --> 01:03:23.064
So, yes, you still have
the functions of a manager.

01:03:23.064 --> 01:03:25.230
They just get broken out
and distributed differently

01:03:25.230 --> 01:03:28.170
and not centralized all in one
person with fuzzy boundaries.

01:03:28.170 --> 01:03:30.128
And they can tell you
what to do and everything

01:03:30.128 --> 01:03:31.290
else all at once.

01:03:31.290 --> 01:03:33.200
AUDIENCE: My question
is how-- so it

01:03:33.200 --> 01:03:35.270
seems to me like--
correct me if I'm

01:03:35.270 --> 01:03:37.780
wrong-- that people that
have a certain skill

01:03:37.780 --> 01:03:40.670
set take on these
particular roles.

01:03:40.670 --> 01:03:44.280
So my question is how do
you develop and grow people

01:03:44.280 --> 01:03:46.370
into other roles
or into other areas

01:03:46.370 --> 01:03:48.170
that they want to go into?

01:03:48.170 --> 01:03:49.086
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah.

01:03:49.086 --> 01:03:50.700
So the first line
of defense there

01:03:50.700 --> 01:03:52.640
is it's everyone's
responsibility

01:03:52.640 --> 01:03:54.000
to deal with their own growth.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.770
And that's what many companies
rely largely on that.

01:03:56.770 --> 01:03:58.595
Some go further and
say, and we want

01:03:58.595 --> 01:03:59.970
to develop cool
internal training

01:03:59.970 --> 01:04:02.550
programs to make it easier
for people to do that.

01:04:02.550 --> 01:04:04.830
But the first ownership
rests with the person.

01:04:04.830 --> 01:04:06.960
So if you want to grow
and develop in new areas.

01:04:06.960 --> 01:04:09.190
Go shop around in
the role marketplace.

01:04:09.190 --> 01:04:12.510
It's what we mean by there's
a space hundreds of roles

01:04:12.510 --> 01:04:13.640
around the company.

01:04:13.640 --> 01:04:14.460
Shop around.

01:04:14.460 --> 01:04:16.620
Go find which ones
excite you and that you

01:04:16.620 --> 01:04:18.470
might be able to start filling.

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:21.200
And see if you can find one
that's maybe 5% of your time,

01:04:21.200 --> 01:04:23.860
but in a new area that forces
you to stretch and grow

01:04:23.860 --> 01:04:24.890
and develop in that way.

01:04:24.890 --> 01:04:27.098
And then take advantage of
whatever training programs

01:04:27.098 --> 01:04:28.910
or whatever else
you can find or get.

01:04:28.910 --> 01:04:31.450
And so it's a much more
organic growth path.

01:04:31.450 --> 01:04:34.080
Instead of you grow
by climbing the rungs

01:04:34.080 --> 01:04:36.600
on the hierarchical
ladder, it's more what

01:04:36.600 --> 01:04:38.490
skills do you want to build?

01:04:38.490 --> 01:04:40.089
Go find ways to
use those skills.

01:04:40.089 --> 01:04:41.630
Go develop in lots
of different ways.

01:04:41.630 --> 01:04:43.920
Whatever makes sense to you.

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:46.000
AUDIENCE: Hey, I
really appreciate

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:48.210
a lot of the philosophy
behind a lot of this.

01:04:48.210 --> 01:04:51.320
I actually think at Google
we do a pretty decent job

01:04:51.320 --> 01:04:53.490
at some of the
principles you recommend.

01:04:53.490 --> 01:04:54.720
Of course, we're not perfect.

01:04:54.720 --> 01:04:56.990
And we don't take it
quite to the same extreme.

01:04:56.990 --> 01:04:59.790
But I think a lot of the things
you were talking about I've

01:04:59.790 --> 01:05:01.630
seen work here pretty well.

01:05:01.630 --> 01:05:04.380
One of the things we try to
do pretty thoroughly at Google

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:06.800
is use evidence and data
to support our management

01:05:06.800 --> 01:05:07.670
decisions.

01:05:07.670 --> 01:05:10.314
What evidence do you have
to suggest that this works?

01:05:10.314 --> 01:05:11.230
BRIAN ROBERTSON: None.

01:05:13.890 --> 01:05:17.770
So I say that jokingly,
although, there's truth to it.

01:05:17.770 --> 01:05:18.460
It's too early.

01:05:18.460 --> 01:05:21.310
We don't have any
good, hard data yet.

01:05:21.310 --> 01:05:23.010
I can't wait till we do.

01:05:23.010 --> 01:05:25.324
But frankly right now,
we have anecdotal data.

01:05:25.324 --> 01:05:26.740
That said, Harvard
Business School

01:05:26.740 --> 01:05:31.114
is doing the first serious
academic study on this.

01:05:31.114 --> 01:05:32.530
The results are
not published yet.

01:05:32.530 --> 01:05:33.850
Although the researcher
tells me they're

01:05:33.850 --> 01:05:35.300
really cool and interesting.

01:05:35.300 --> 01:05:36.980
So I can't wait till that's out.

01:05:36.980 --> 01:05:38.400
They're setting
up a second study

01:05:38.400 --> 01:05:39.650
they are looking at doing now.

01:05:39.650 --> 01:05:42.250
So we will have
data at some point.

01:05:42.250 --> 01:05:44.580
That said, this is
a really tough thing

01:05:44.580 --> 01:05:47.094
to get that kind
of hard data on.

01:05:47.094 --> 01:05:48.010
I have anecdotal data.

01:05:48.010 --> 01:05:49.630
I have one company
said, our revenue

01:05:49.630 --> 01:05:51.390
tripled after we
adopted Holacracy.

01:05:51.390 --> 01:05:53.350
And that may be--
I'm sure it's true.

01:05:53.350 --> 01:05:55.660
But how do you make
the causal link

01:05:55.660 --> 01:05:58.340
between Holacracy and
revenue tripling, really?

01:05:58.340 --> 01:05:59.810
Like did you launch
a new product?

01:05:59.810 --> 01:06:01.890
Maybe that was--

01:06:01.890 --> 01:06:03.770
So it's so hard
to make that link.

01:06:03.770 --> 01:06:07.440
Instead, the data I tend
to encourage people to use.

01:06:07.440 --> 01:06:08.786
And this is a form of data.

01:06:08.786 --> 01:06:09.910
But it's a subjective form.

01:06:09.910 --> 01:06:13.020
It's tune in to your
internal experience.

01:06:13.020 --> 01:06:16.810
Is it easier or harder to use
your skills to drive change

01:06:16.810 --> 01:06:17.936
in this company?

01:06:17.936 --> 01:06:19.560
Because if everyone
involved is saying,

01:06:19.560 --> 01:06:21.060
hey, we tried this
for a few months.

01:06:21.060 --> 01:06:25.090
And what we notice is we can
use whatever tensions we sense.

01:06:25.090 --> 01:06:27.120
We can get them
processed into something

01:06:27.120 --> 01:06:30.250
more quickly with less obstacles
and less waste in the way.

01:06:30.250 --> 01:06:34.170
That should translate into
better results as best we can.

01:06:34.170 --> 01:06:36.280
And I think there's
a lot of wisdom

01:06:36.280 --> 01:06:38.440
in that internal sensing.

01:06:38.440 --> 01:06:41.840
So in the absence of actual
hard data that I trust,

01:06:41.840 --> 01:06:44.775
that's the data point I tell
the people to use-- tune

01:06:44.775 --> 01:06:46.670
in internally.

01:06:46.670 --> 01:06:49.330
AUDIENCE: Leaders who
might be playing around

01:06:49.330 --> 01:06:51.460
with the idea of
potentially doing this.

01:06:51.460 --> 01:06:54.850
Following Zappos's transition,
it seemed like at one point

01:06:54.850 --> 01:06:56.130
they had one foot in.

01:06:56.130 --> 01:06:59.020
And now they have both feet in.

01:06:59.020 --> 01:07:01.810
If Google were to do
something like this

01:07:01.810 --> 01:07:04.490
with the version of the
constitution that you have now,

01:07:04.490 --> 01:07:07.490
would you recommend all
or nothing approach?

01:07:07.490 --> 01:07:10.180
Or could you do this in
small, meaningful ways?

01:07:10.180 --> 01:07:13.150
BRIAN ROBERTSON: Yeah, so the
answer is a little nuanced.

01:07:13.150 --> 01:07:15.420
I'd recommend very similar
to what Zappos did.

01:07:15.420 --> 01:07:17.750
Their footsteps are
excellent ones to follow.

01:07:17.750 --> 01:07:19.590
And they've done an amazing job.

01:07:19.590 --> 01:07:23.520
What they did was first they
adopted all of Holacracy

01:07:23.520 --> 01:07:26.890
in part of the company, which is
actually way better than trying

01:07:26.890 --> 01:07:29.870
to adopt part of Holacracy
in all of the company.

01:07:29.870 --> 01:07:33.040
So think of it like a
new sport like soccer.

01:07:33.040 --> 01:07:35.400
You probably don't get
to play World Cup soccer

01:07:35.400 --> 01:07:37.920
by starting and saying, all
right, let's master kicking

01:07:37.920 --> 01:07:40.530
the ball and nothing else,
just kicking the ball.

01:07:40.530 --> 01:07:41.530
And then the next thing.

01:07:41.530 --> 01:07:43.690
Probably you get there
by playing soccer

01:07:43.690 --> 01:07:45.160
at six-year-old level.

01:07:45.160 --> 01:07:48.212
But you're still playing by
all the rules of the game.

01:07:48.212 --> 01:07:50.170
So better to play by all
the rules of the game,

01:07:50.170 --> 01:07:51.882
even in just one
team or department.

01:07:51.882 --> 01:07:53.090
And Zappos started with that.

01:07:53.090 --> 01:07:54.464
They started with
one department.

01:07:54.464 --> 01:07:56.910
They played by all the
rules as best they could.

01:07:56.910 --> 01:07:58.910
Now in terms of one foot
in one foot out though,

01:07:58.910 --> 01:08:00.790
even playing by all
the rules doesn't

01:08:00.790 --> 01:08:04.660
mean you've adopted everything
that you eventually will.

01:08:04.660 --> 01:08:06.780
So to use another metaphor,
think of Holacracy

01:08:06.780 --> 01:08:08.480
like an operating system.

01:08:08.480 --> 01:08:09.930
It's a platform.

01:08:09.930 --> 01:08:13.160
But it doesn't give you
all the apps you need.

01:08:13.160 --> 01:08:17.569
So you guys know-- a good
platform goes a long way.

01:08:17.569 --> 01:08:18.800
Apps matter a lot.

01:08:18.800 --> 01:08:20.000
You need both.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:22.340
Holacracy is just
the operating system.

01:08:22.340 --> 01:08:24.670
The apps that you will
eventually build on top of it

01:08:24.670 --> 01:08:26.680
are things like how
do we do compensation?

01:08:26.680 --> 01:08:28.920
Holacracy constitution
does not tell you anything

01:08:28.920 --> 01:08:30.520
about how to do compensation.

01:08:30.520 --> 01:08:33.470
It tells you how to decide
how to do compensation,

01:08:33.470 --> 01:08:34.910
but not what to do with it.

01:08:34.910 --> 01:08:38.160
Nor does it cover firing,
budgeting, performance

01:08:38.160 --> 01:08:40.740
management-- all these other
processes that you need.

01:08:40.740 --> 01:08:42.887
Those are the apps of business.

01:08:42.887 --> 01:08:45.220
And when you first start
running with this new operating

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:47.023
system, the best thing to do.

01:08:47.023 --> 01:08:48.189
And this is what Zappos did.

01:08:48.189 --> 01:08:50.399
Keep all your apps as they are.

01:08:50.399 --> 01:08:53.350
Otherwise, you're just
changing too much all at once.

01:08:53.350 --> 01:08:54.640
So bite off a piece at a time.

01:08:54.640 --> 01:08:56.300
You do need to adopt the
full operating system.

01:08:56.300 --> 01:08:58.029
You don't run half
Windows half Linux.

01:08:58.029 --> 01:08:59.438
It doesn't work.

01:08:59.438 --> 01:09:00.479
You're either on Windows.

01:09:00.479 --> 01:09:01.290
You're on Linux.

01:09:01.290 --> 01:09:03.330
You're on Mac OS X, whatever.

01:09:03.330 --> 01:09:04.220
But you can do that.

01:09:04.220 --> 01:09:06.803
When I first-- I switched from
Windows to Mac a few years ago.

01:09:06.803 --> 01:09:08.970
And when I did, I
installed parallels.

01:09:08.970 --> 01:09:11.834
And I ran most of my apps--
the same ones I did on Windows.

01:09:11.834 --> 01:09:14.250
And that was a nice, graceful
path-- new operating system,

01:09:14.250 --> 01:09:15.819
still used Quicken and
all these other apps

01:09:15.819 --> 01:09:16.840
that were Windows-based.

01:09:16.840 --> 01:09:18.798
And then eventually I
started upgrading my apps

01:09:18.798 --> 01:09:19.890
and getting onto Mac apps.

01:09:19.890 --> 01:09:21.600
And that was a much easier path.

01:09:21.600 --> 01:09:24.469
So at the same time, you're
going to feel some pain.

01:09:24.469 --> 01:09:26.510
And that's what Zappos
talked about with one foot

01:09:26.510 --> 01:09:27.270
in, one foot out.

01:09:27.270 --> 01:09:28.920
They were doing
all of holocracy--

01:09:28.920 --> 01:09:31.430
first in part of the company--
then in all of the company.

01:09:31.430 --> 01:09:32.971
But they were still
running backwards

01:09:32.971 --> 01:09:36.569
compatible apps or barely
backwards compatible apps.

01:09:36.569 --> 01:09:39.050
So their compensation
system was still

01:09:39.050 --> 01:09:41.188
relying on what looked like
a management hierarchy.

01:09:41.188 --> 01:09:43.229
That's tough when you're
running in this new mode

01:09:43.229 --> 01:09:45.529
at the core of your
operating system that doesn't

01:09:45.529 --> 01:09:46.620
use management hierarchy.

01:09:46.620 --> 01:09:48.319
But your comp system still does.

01:09:48.319 --> 01:09:50.990
It's hard to tell people own
your autonomy and your role.

01:09:50.990 --> 01:09:53.200
The boss can't tell you
what to do when the boss can

01:09:53.200 --> 01:09:56.330
set your pay or fire you,
which was the one foot in,

01:09:56.330 --> 01:09:57.000
one foot out.

01:09:57.000 --> 01:09:59.500
So companies when they adopt
Holacracy will start there.

01:09:59.500 --> 01:10:02.700
But then, eventually, they will
feel some tension about that.

01:10:02.700 --> 01:10:04.724
And then they start
working on the apps.

01:10:04.724 --> 01:10:06.140
And they'll start
either designing

01:10:06.140 --> 01:10:07.520
their own compensation
system that

01:10:07.520 --> 01:10:09.220
is more Holacracy
compatible and doesn't

01:10:09.220 --> 01:10:11.930
rely on a management hierarchy
and firing processes and all

01:10:11.930 --> 01:10:12.510
these.

01:10:12.510 --> 01:10:14.650
Or they'll go out
into the open source

01:10:14.650 --> 01:10:16.630
community of apps
that are out there

01:10:16.630 --> 01:10:18.076
and find one that
works for them.

01:10:18.076 --> 01:10:19.700
So we have an approach
to compensation,

01:10:19.700 --> 01:10:22.040
for example, that's very
Holacracy compatible.

01:10:22.040 --> 01:10:24.010
It's also similar
to what Zappos does.

01:10:24.010 --> 01:10:27.614
You can steal ours or
vary it or whatever.

01:10:27.614 --> 01:10:28.780
AUDIENCE: One more question.

01:10:28.780 --> 01:10:30.200
And actually, just
for the record,

01:10:30.200 --> 01:10:33.460
we also at Google-- our
managers don't set our pay.

01:10:33.460 --> 01:10:36.210
So I think there are some things
as Mary Kate was mentioning

01:10:36.210 --> 01:10:39.440
that are already applied at
Google just we have something

01:10:39.440 --> 01:10:43.320
in between a Holacractic version
and a feudal system version.

01:10:43.320 --> 01:10:45.050
But one more question
about managers.

01:10:45.050 --> 01:10:47.526
So I think back in the
day, Larry and Sergey

01:10:47.526 --> 01:10:48.400
didn't like managers.

01:10:48.400 --> 01:10:50.230
And they're like, well, let's
just try not having managers.

01:10:50.230 --> 01:10:51.560
And they experimented with that.

01:10:51.560 --> 01:10:53.101
And they found that
a lot of Googlers

01:10:53.101 --> 01:10:55.240
really missed having managers.

01:10:55.240 --> 01:10:56.760
And the thinking
here is if you have

01:10:56.760 --> 01:10:58.620
a good manager,
that someone who's

01:10:58.620 --> 01:11:00.510
in your corner-- they
are a people manager.

01:11:00.510 --> 01:11:02.090
They're not like
a project manager.

01:11:02.090 --> 01:11:05.000
So there's someone-- that's
a person whose job it

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:07.590
is to check in with you and say,
how are your projects going?

01:11:07.590 --> 01:11:09.340
Let's talk about your
career development--

01:11:09.340 --> 01:11:12.540
how do you feel about
well-being, work-life balance.

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:14.959
And so I just wonder
have you surveyed people

01:11:14.959 --> 01:11:15.750
at these companies.

01:11:15.750 --> 01:11:17.291
And have you found
that anyone really

01:11:17.291 --> 01:11:19.710
misses having a more--
someone that's really

01:11:19.710 --> 01:11:22.200
in their corner whose job
it is to care about them

01:11:22.200 --> 01:11:24.700
and their careers, their work?

01:11:24.700 --> 01:11:26.310
BRIAN ROBERTSON:
Yeah, definitely.

01:11:26.310 --> 01:11:29.175
It is difficult to go
from having that-- having

01:11:29.175 --> 01:11:31.650
that parent-like
figure, especially

01:11:31.650 --> 01:11:32.880
if you've got a good one.

01:11:32.880 --> 01:11:35.600
If you've got a bad
parent, that's different--

01:11:35.600 --> 01:11:37.020
the same growing up.

01:11:37.020 --> 01:11:39.290
It's really comforting to
live in your parents' house,

01:11:39.290 --> 01:11:40.550
have them take care
of your needs--

01:11:40.550 --> 01:11:42.310
know that you don't have
to brave the world of being

01:11:42.310 --> 01:11:44.990
an adult yourself fully because
you've got a good parent.

01:11:44.990 --> 01:11:46.450
And I think a lot
of our attempts

01:11:46.450 --> 01:11:48.400
to develop organizations
today rely on trying

01:11:48.400 --> 01:11:50.370
to get better parents.

01:11:50.370 --> 01:11:53.516
In other words, let's get
better leaders, better managers

01:11:53.516 --> 01:11:55.390
in place so that they're
good parents instead

01:11:55.390 --> 01:11:58.260
of the bad manager parent.

01:11:58.260 --> 01:11:59.520
And I think that can go.

01:11:59.520 --> 01:12:02.590
To a large extent, that can
improve things-- that can help.

01:12:02.590 --> 01:12:05.787
But at some point, if you really
want to take that next leap,

01:12:05.787 --> 01:12:07.370
you need to move out
of home and learn

01:12:07.370 --> 01:12:10.750
to be an adult that doesn't
need the caretaking protective

01:12:10.750 --> 01:12:11.420
parent.

01:12:11.420 --> 01:12:13.510
It doesn't mean you don't have
a relationship with your parent.

01:12:13.510 --> 01:12:15.580
It doesn't mean you don't have
peers that can support you--

01:12:15.580 --> 01:12:18.204
that you can lean on-- that are
on your side-- that are helping

01:12:18.204 --> 01:12:19.440
you-- that are mentoring you.

01:12:19.440 --> 01:12:21.410
You can have all of those
things without having

01:12:21.410 --> 01:12:23.730
it be parent-child dynamic.

01:12:23.730 --> 01:12:25.590
It can be adult to
adult and peer to peer.

01:12:25.590 --> 01:12:27.190
So we have a role in my company.

01:12:27.190 --> 01:12:28.720
It's called partner-partner.

01:12:28.720 --> 01:12:31.820
So it's a partner's partner.

01:12:31.820 --> 01:12:34.470
And that role is there as
a mentor for new people

01:12:34.470 --> 01:12:36.630
as they come into
this organization.

01:12:36.630 --> 01:12:39.640
So there's lots of ways that
you can support each other

01:12:39.640 --> 01:12:42.370
as well as the informal
that always happens.

01:12:42.370 --> 01:12:46.290
But there is that big shift from
parent-child dynamics to being

01:12:46.290 --> 01:12:48.470
an adult out in the world.

01:12:48.470 --> 01:12:49.800
And that is hard.

01:12:49.800 --> 01:12:52.800
You see a lot of people that
are uncomfortable with that

01:12:52.800 --> 01:12:53.710
at first.

01:12:53.710 --> 01:12:56.550
And some of them don't want it
so much that they will leave.

01:12:56.550 --> 01:13:00.230
You will lose some people when
you apply a system like this.

01:13:00.230 --> 01:13:01.790
It's really hard.

01:13:01.790 --> 01:13:04.040
Some people choose to stay
at home until their parents

01:13:04.040 --> 01:13:07.178
literally kick them out.

01:13:07.178 --> 01:13:09.310
And some people don't.

01:13:09.310 --> 01:13:12.140
I know plenty of people
at are approaching 30

01:13:12.140 --> 01:13:14.210
and still live at
home as a child

01:13:14.210 --> 01:13:15.850
under their parents' roof.

01:13:15.850 --> 01:13:18.080
So it's tough.

01:13:18.080 --> 01:13:21.320
And yet there's also
so much that happens

01:13:21.320 --> 01:13:22.820
in somebody's
internal development

01:13:22.820 --> 01:13:25.560
even when they really do
leave behind the sheltering

01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:28.530
comfort and safety of that
parent-like manager figure

01:13:28.530 --> 01:13:30.850
and own their
authority, be an adult,

01:13:30.850 --> 01:13:32.694
still get mentoring
and all that.

01:13:32.694 --> 01:13:34.610
The other thing I'd say
is when most companies

01:13:34.610 --> 01:13:37.249
attempt to throw out
managers, the biggest

01:13:37.249 --> 01:13:38.790
mistake they make
is not replacing it

01:13:38.790 --> 01:13:40.180
with an alternate structure.

01:13:40.180 --> 01:13:43.202
And that is not what
Holacracy is about.

01:13:43.202 --> 01:13:44.160
Some companies do that.

01:13:44.160 --> 01:13:46.010
A few even make it
work like valve makes

01:13:46.010 --> 01:13:47.424
that work actually pretty well.

01:13:47.424 --> 01:13:49.590
Although they have a lot
of politics because there's

01:13:49.590 --> 01:13:50.315
no other process.

01:13:50.315 --> 01:13:53.140
So politics kind of rule.

01:13:53.140 --> 01:13:54.400
But it's really hard.

01:13:54.400 --> 01:13:55.580
Holacracy is not that.

01:13:55.580 --> 01:13:56.910
It's more structured, not less.

01:13:56.910 --> 01:13:59.034
It's just a completely
different kind of structure,

01:13:59.034 --> 01:14:01.851
more like a city that lets
more of a dynamic order emerge.

01:14:01.851 --> 01:14:03.600
So you've got to replace
it with something

01:14:03.600 --> 01:14:05.289
or you don't get
a nice replacement

01:14:05.289 --> 01:14:06.330
for management structure.

01:14:06.330 --> 01:14:09.330
You get something that often
is a big step backwards

01:14:09.330 --> 01:14:12.740
or at least a side step into
a completely chaotic space.

01:14:12.740 --> 01:14:15.677
So replace it with something
would be my lesson.

01:14:15.677 --> 01:14:17.760
